  // ───────────────────── L10: Word problems — circles, arcs ────────────
  {
    id: 'L10',
    title: 'Lesson 10 · Word problems · circles & sectors',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Reading the situation, picking the formula',
      body: [
        'Real-world circle questions usually hand you a description and a few numbers. Your job is to (1) draw or imagine the shape, (2) decide which dimension is the radius (or diameter, or arc length, or sector angle), and (3) pick the right formula.',
        'A wheel ROLLING one full turn covers a distance equal to its CIRCUMFERENCE. If it turns N times, it covers N \\times C.',
        'A sector with a small angle (think of a slice of cake or a fan) uses sector area = \\frac{\\theta}{360} \\times \\pi r^2.',
        'A circular boundary on a flag, pond, or sign uses circumference = \\pi d.',
        'Always re-read the question to check whether the answer should be exact (in \\pi) or a decimal to a stated number of significant figures.',
      ],
      example: 'A pizza has diameter 30 cm. Its area is \\pi \\times 15^2 = 225 \\pi \\approx 707 cm^2.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A circular pond has diameter 4 m. A 1-m-wide path runs around its outside. Area of the PATH in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['5 \\pi m^2', '4 \\pi m^2', '\\pi m^2', '9 \\pi m^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Outer radius 3, inner radius 2. \\pi(3^2 - 2^2) = \\pi(9-4) = 5 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A car wheel has diameter 60 cm. How many full turns does it make over 100 metres? (3 s.f.)',
        options: ['53.1', '167', '300', '1.67'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'C = \\pi \\times 0.6 = 1.885 m. 100 / 1.885 \\approx 53.05.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A piece of rope is wound 15 times around a cylindrical pipe of diameter 50 cm. Length of rope in metres to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['23.6 m', '7.85 m', '47.1 m', '78.5 m'], correct: 0,
        solution: '15 \\times \\pi \\times 0.5 = 7.5 \\pi \\approx 23.56 m.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A pizza of radius 12 cm is cut into 8 equal slices. Area of one slice in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['18 \\pi cm^2', '12 \\pi cm^2', '9 \\pi cm^2', '24 \\pi cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{8} \\times \\pi \\times 144 = 18 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A circular cake has area 254 cm^2 (to 3 s.f.). Approximate radius (\\pi \\approx 3.14)?',
        options: ['9 cm', '4.5 cm', '18 cm', '12 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'r = \\sqrt{254/\\pi} \\approx \\sqrt{80.9} \\approx 9 cm.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A sector of a disc of radius 1.2 m subtends an angle of 40^\\circ at the centre. Area to 2 d.p.?',
        options: ['0.50 m^2', '1.51 m^2', '0.84 m^2', '0.25 m^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{40}{360} \\times \\pi \\times 1.44 = \\frac{1}{9} \\times 4.5239 \\approx 0.503.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: '16 identical circles fit in a square sheet 0.4 m on a side (4 by 4 grid). Each circle has the largest possible diameter. Diameter of each circle?',
        options: ['0.10 m', '0.05 m', '0.40 m', '0.20 m'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.4 / 4 = 0.1 m.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: '… (continued) Total area of the 16 circles in m^2 to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['0.126 m^2', '0.0314 m^2', '0.503 m^2', '0.0628 m^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '16 \\times \\pi \\times 0.05^2 = 0.04 \\pi \\approx 0.1257.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A circular drain cover has diameter 60 cm. Cost of paint is $2 per 100 cm^2. Approximate cost to paint one face? (\\pi \\approx 3.14)',
        options: ['$56.55', '$5.66', '$28.27', '$11.31'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'A = \\pi \\times 30^2 \\approx 2827.4 cm^2; cost = 28.274 \\times $2 \\approx $56.55.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A beach umbrella is made of 8 identical sectors of radius 1.2 m and angle 40^\\circ each, joined to form an octagon-shaped fan top. Total area to 2 d.p.?',
        options: ['4.02 m^2', '0.50 m^2', '4.52 m^2', '0.16 m^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Each sector \\approx 0.503 m^2; 8 \\times 0.503 \\approx 4.02 m^2 (covers \\frac{8 \\times 40}{360} = \\frac{8}{9} of a circle).' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L11: Nets of 3D solids ────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L11',
    title: 'Lesson 11 · Nets of 3D solids',
    teach: {
      heading: 'A NET is a flat-pack version of a 3D solid',
      body: [
        'A NET is a 2D shape that can be folded along the dotted edges to make a 3D solid. Its total area equals the SURFACE AREA of that solid.',
        'The net of a CUBOID has 6 rectangles: top and bottom (same), front and back (same), left and right (same).',
        'The net of a CYLINDER has two circles (the two ends) plus one rectangle whose length equals the cylinder\\u2019s circumference and whose width equals its height.',
        'The net of a TRIANGULAR PRISM has two triangles (the ends) and three rectangles (the sides).',
        'When you imagine folding a net, edges that touch each other after folding must be the SAME length. Use this to spot wrong nets.',
      ],
      example: 'A cuboid 5 by 3 by 2 has 6 faces: two 5x3, two 5x2, two 3x2. Net surface area = 2(15) + 2(10) + 2(6) = 62 cm^2.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'How many faces does a cuboid have?',
        options: ['6', '4', '8', '12'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Top, bottom, front, back, left, right.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'How many EDGES does a cube have?',
        options: ['12', '8', '6', '24'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'A cube: 12 edges, 6 faces, 8 vertices.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'The net of a cylinder is made of …',
        options: ['Two circles and one rectangle', 'Two circles and two rectangles', 'One circle and one rectangle', 'Three rectangles'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Top + bottom (circles) + curved surface (a rectangle when unrolled).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A triangular prism has cross-section a triangle. Its net has …',
        options: ['Two triangles and three rectangles', 'Three triangles and two rectangles', 'Six triangles', 'Two triangles and one rectangle'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Two triangular ends + three rectangles for the three side faces.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cylinder has radius 5 cm and height 12 cm. The rectangle in its net has dimensions …',
        options: ['10 \\pi cm by 12 cm', '5 \\pi cm by 12 cm', '5 cm by 12 cm', '10 cm by 12 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Length = circumference = 2 \\pi r = 10 \\pi; width = height = 12.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cube has surface area 96 cm^2. What is the side length?',
        options: ['4 cm', '6 cm', '16 cm', '8 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: '6 a^2 = 96 \\to a^2 = 16 \\to a = 4.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A square-based pyramid has 4 triangular faces and 1 square face. Its net has …',
        options: ['Four triangles around one square', 'Three triangles around one square', 'Five triangles', 'Four squares around a triangle'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'One base square + four triangular faces.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A regular tetrahedron has 4 equilateral-triangle faces. Net?',
        options: ['Four equilateral triangles joined edge to edge', 'Three triangles in a row', 'A square and four triangles', 'Six triangles'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Just the four faces unfolded.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cuboid has dimensions 4 cm, 3 cm, 2 cm. Its surface area in cm^2?',
        options: ['52', '24', '36', '60'], correct: 0,
        solution: '2(4 \\times 3 + 4 \\times 2 + 3 \\times 2) = 2(12+8+6) = 52.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Which of the following is NOT the net of any cube? (A) cross-shape with 4 in a row + 2 on opposite sides; (B) 6 squares in a single 3-by-2 rectangle.',
        options: ['B', 'A', 'Both are valid', 'Neither is valid'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Six squares laid out 3-by-2 do not fold into a cube — opposite sides overlap. The cross fold works.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L12: Cuboids and prisms ───────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L12',
    title: 'Lesson 12 · Cuboids & prisms',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Volume = cross-section \\times length',
      body: [
        'A PRISM is a solid with the same cross-section all the way along its length. A cuboid is a special prism with a rectangular cross-section.',
        'Volume of a prism = area of cross-section \\times length.',
        'Cuboid: V = \\ell \\times w \\times h.',
        'Surface area = (perimeter of cross-section \\times length) + (2 \\times area of cross-section). For a cuboid this is 2(\\ell w + \\ell h + w h).',
        'Watch units: cm^3 for cm-lengths, m^3 for m-lengths.',
      ],
      example: 'Cuboid 5 by 3 by 2 cm. V = 30 cm^3. SA = 2(15 + 10 + 6) = 62 cm^2.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a cuboid 4 cm by 3 cm by 2 cm?',
        options: ['24 cm^3', '9 cm^3', '12 cm^3', '48 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '4 \\times 3 \\times 2 = 24.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a cube of side 5 cm?',
        options: ['125 cm^3', '25 cm^3', '15 cm^3', '75 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '5^3 = 125.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Surface area of a cube of side 4 m?',
        options: ['96 m^2', '16 m^2', '64 m^2', '24 m^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '6 \\times 16 = 96.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Cuboid: length 8 cm, width 5 cm, height 3 cm. Surface area?',
        options: ['158 cm^2', '120 cm^2', '79 cm^2', '46 cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '2(40 + 24 + 15) = 158.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A triangular prism has a right-triangle cross-section with legs 3 cm and 4 cm. Length 10 cm. Volume?',
        options: ['60 cm^3', '120 cm^3', '30 cm^3', '90 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Cross-section area = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 3 \\times 4 = 6. V = 6 \\times 10 = 60.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Volume in cm^3 of a cuboid 12 cm by 4 cm by 5 cm?', answer: 240,
        solution: '12 \\times 4 \\times 5 = 240.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Volume in cm^3 of a triangular prism with cross-section a triangle of base 6 cm, height 4 cm, and length 9 cm?', answer: 108,
        solution: 'Cross = 12; V = 12 \\times 9 = 108.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A rectangular crate measures 1.2 m by 0.5 m by 2.5 m. Volume in m^3?',
        options: ['1.5', '0.6', '4.2', '0.15'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1.2 \\times 0.5 \\times 2.5 = 1.5.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A storage room is 20 m by 8 m by 8 m. Number of 1 m by 0.5 m by 2.5 m boxes that fit (assuming perfect packing)?',
        options: ['1024', '512', '2048', '256'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Room: 1280 m^3. Box: 1.25 m^3. 1280/1.25 = 1024.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A pencil case is a triangular prism: cross-section equilateral triangle of side 6 cm (area \\approx 15.59 cm^2), length 20 cm. Volume to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['312 cm^3', '120 cm^3', '156 cm^3', '624 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '15.59 \\times 20 \\approx 311.8 \\to 312.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L13: Cylinders ────────────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L13',
    title: 'Lesson 13 · Cylinders',
    teach: {
      heading: 'V = \\pi r^2 h, curved SA = 2 \\pi r h',
      body: [
        'A CYLINDER is a prism with a CIRCULAR cross-section. So volume = area of cross-section \\times length = \\pi r^2 h.',
        'When you unroll the curved surface, you get a rectangle whose length is the circumference (2 \\pi r) and whose height is h. So curved surface area = 2 \\pi r h.',
        'TOTAL surface area (closed at both ends) = 2 \\pi r h + 2 \\pi r^2 (the two end discs add 2 \\pi r^2).',
        'For an OPEN-TOPPED cylinder (e.g. a glass), the top disc is missing, so SA = 2 \\pi r h + \\pi r^2.',
      ],
      example: 'Cylinder r = 3 cm, h = 10 cm. V = \\pi \\times 9 \\times 10 = 90 \\pi cm^3 \\approx 282.7 cm^3. Curved SA = 2 \\pi \\times 3 \\times 10 = 60 \\pi cm^2 \\approx 188.5 cm^2.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a cylinder r = 2 cm, h = 5 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['20 \\pi cm^3', '10 \\pi cm^3', '40 \\pi cm^3', '4 \\pi cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\pi \\times 4 \\times 5 = 20 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a cylinder r = 4 cm, h = 10 cm to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['503 cm^3', '251 cm^3', '160 cm^3', '125 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\pi \\times 16 \\times 10 = 160 \\pi \\approx 502.65.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Curved SA of a cylinder r = 3 cm, h = 8 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['48 \\pi cm^2', '24 \\pi cm^2', '72 \\pi cm^2', '9 \\pi cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '2 \\pi \\times 3 \\times 8 = 48 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'TOTAL SA of a closed cylinder r = 3 cm, h = 8 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['66 \\pi cm^2', '48 \\pi cm^2', '57 \\pi cm^2', '90 \\pi cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '2 \\pi r h + 2 \\pi r^2 = 48 \\pi + 18 \\pi = 66 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cylindrical drain has diameter 1.2 m and length 30 m. Volume in m^3 to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['33.9 m^3', '113 m^3', '11.3 m^3', '67.9 m^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'r = 0.6; V = \\pi \\times 0.36 \\times 30 \\approx 33.93.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Volume of a cylinder r = 5 cm, h = 14 cm to 3 s.f. in cm^3?', answer: 1100, tol: 5,
        solution: '\\pi \\times 25 \\times 14 = 350 \\pi \\approx 1099.6 \\to 1100.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cylindrical tank has radius 1.5 m and height 4 m. How many litres of water does it hold? (1 m^3 = 1000 L)',
        options: ['28 274 L', '2 827 L', '18 850 L', '6 283 L'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'V = \\pi \\times 2.25 \\times 4 \\approx 28.274 m^3 = 28 274 L.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A 32 cm long cardboard cylinder has radius 2.5 cm. CURVED surface area in cm^2 to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['503', '251', '628', '160'], correct: 0,
        solution: '2 \\pi \\times 2.5 \\times 32 = 160 \\pi \\approx 502.65.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A clock case is a cuboid 8 cm by 6 cm by 6 cm with a cylindrical hole of r = 2 cm running through it (length 8 cm). Volume of glass to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['188 cm^3', '288 cm^3', '100 cm^3', '212 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '8 \\times 6 \\times 6 - \\pi \\times 4 \\times 8 = 288 - 100.53 = 187.5.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'A cylinder has volume 200 \\pi cm^3 and radius 5 cm. Find its height in cm.', answer: 8,
        solution: '\\pi \\times 25 \\times h = 200 \\pi \\to h = 8.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L14: Pyramids ────────────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L14',
    title: 'Lesson 14 · Pyramids',
    teach: {
      heading: 'V = \\frac{1}{3} \\times base area \\times perpendicular height',
      body: [
        'A PYRAMID has a polygon base and triangular faces meeting at a point called the APEX.',
        'Volume of any pyramid = \\frac{1}{3} \\times (area of base) \\times (perpendicular height from apex to base).',
        'Be careful: PERPENDICULAR height is the straight-down distance from the apex to the base, NOT the slant length along a face.',
        'Surface area = base area + sum of triangular-face areas. Each triangular face uses the SLANT height (along the face), not the perpendicular height.',
      ],
      example: 'Square-based pyramid with base side 6 cm and perpendicular height 9 cm. V = \\frac{1}{3} \\times 36 \\times 9 = 108 cm^3.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a pyramid with square base side 6 cm and perpendicular height 5 cm?',
        options: ['60 cm^3', '180 cm^3', '30 cm^3', '120 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 36 \\times 5 = 60.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a pyramid with rectangular base 4 cm by 3 cm and perpendicular height 9 cm?',
        options: ['36 cm^3', '108 cm^3', '12 cm^3', '72 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 12 \\times 9 = 36.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A pyramid has square base side 10 cm and volume 100 cm^3. Perpendicular height?',
        options: ['3 cm', '10 cm', '1 cm', '30 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'h = \\frac{3V}{base} = \\frac{300}{100} = 3.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A pyramid has triangular base of area 18 cm^2 and perpendicular height 7 cm. Volume?',
        options: ['42 cm^3', '126 cm^3', '21 cm^3', '12.6 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 18 \\times 7 = 42.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'The Great Pyramid of Giza has a square base of side 230 m and perpendicular height 138.5 m. Original volume to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['2 440 000 m^3', '7 320 000 m^3', '813 000 m^3', '4 880 000 m^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 230^2 \\times 138.5 = \\frac{1}{3} \\times 52900 \\times 138.5 \\approx 2 442 716.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Volume in cm^3 of a square-based pyramid, base side 9 cm, perpendicular height 12 cm.', answer: 324,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 81 \\times 12 = 324.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A square-based pyramid with base side 4 cm and slant height 5 cm. Total surface area (incl. base)?',
        options: ['56 cm^2', '40 cm^2', '36 cm^2', '64 cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Base 16 + 4 triangles each \\frac{1}{2} \\times 4 \\times 5 = 10. Total 16 + 40 = 56.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A pyramid with regular hexagonal base of area 60 cm^2 and perpendicular height 10 cm. Volume?',
        options: ['200 cm^3', '600 cm^3', '300 cm^3', '60 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 60 \\times 10 = 200.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A pyramid is cut PARALLEL to its base half-way up; the bottom piece is called a FRUSTUM. The frustum\\u2019s volume equals the WHOLE pyramid minus …',
        options: ['the small upper pyramid', 'half the original pyramid', 'twice the upper pyramid', 'the apex point'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'V_{frustum} = V_{whole} - V_{upper}.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'A pyramid of height 6 cm and square base 12 cm is cut in half parallel to its base; the upper pyramid has half the height (3 cm) and base side 6 cm. VOLUME of the FRUSTUM in cm^3?', answer: 252,
        solution: 'V_{whole} = \\frac{1}{3} \\times 144 \\times 6 = 288. V_{upper} = \\frac{1}{3} \\times 36 \\times 3 = 36. Frustum = 288 - 36 = 252.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L15: Cones and spheres ────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L15',
    title: 'Lesson 15 · Cones & spheres',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Cone V = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi r^2 h,  Sphere V = \\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3',
      body: [
        'A CONE is a pyramid with a circular base. Its volume is therefore V = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi r^2 h.',
        'Curved surface area of a cone = \\pi r l, where l is the SLANT height (along the slope, not the perpendicular height). Total SA = \\pi r l + \\pi r^2 (curved + base).',
        'The slant, perpendicular height, and radius form a right triangle: l^2 = r^2 + h^2 (Pythagoras).',
        'A SPHERE has volume V = \\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3 and surface area SA = 4 \\pi r^2.',
        'A HEMISPHERE is half a sphere: V = \\frac{2}{3} \\pi r^3 and curved surface area = 2 \\pi r^2.',
      ],
      example: 'A cone with r = 3 cm, h = 4 cm. Slant l = \\sqrt{9 + 16} = 5. V = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi \\times 9 \\times 4 = 12 \\pi \\approx 37.7 cm^3. Curved SA = \\pi \\times 3 \\times 5 = 15 \\pi cm^2.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a cone with r = 3 cm, h = 5 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['15 \\pi cm^3', '45 \\pi cm^3', '5 \\pi cm^3', '9 \\pi cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\pi \\times 9 \\times 5 = 15 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a sphere of radius 3 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['36 \\pi cm^3', '12 \\pi cm^3', '27 \\pi cm^3', '108 \\pi cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{3} \\pi \\times 27 = 36 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Surface area of a sphere of radius 5 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['100 \\pi cm^2', '25 \\pi cm^2', '50 \\pi cm^2', '4 \\pi cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '4 \\pi r^2 = 100 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cone has r = 6 cm and slant length 10 cm. Curved surface area in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['60 \\pi cm^2', '36 \\pi cm^2', '120 \\pi cm^2', '96 \\pi cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\pi r l = 60 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cone has r = 6 cm and perpendicular height 8 cm. SLANT height?',
        options: ['10 cm', '14 cm', '12 cm', '7 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\sqrt{36 + 64} = \\sqrt{100} = 10.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Volume of a hemisphere of radius 3 cm in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['18 \\pi cm^3', '36 \\pi cm^3', '9 \\pi cm^3', '12 \\pi cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{2}{3} \\pi \\times 27 = 18 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A beach ball has radius 20 cm. Surface area in cm^2 to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['5030', '1260', '33500', '2010'], correct: 0,
        solution: '4 \\pi \\times 400 = 1600 \\pi \\approx 5026.55.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Volume of a sphere of radius 6 cm in cm^3 to 3 s.f.', answer: 905, tol: 5,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{3} \\pi \\times 216 = 288 \\pi \\approx 904.78.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A solid cone has r = 5 cm and slant height 13 cm. TOTAL SA in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['90 \\pi cm^2', '65 \\pi cm^2', '25 \\pi cm^2', '169 \\pi cm^2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\pi r l + \\pi r^2 = 65 \\pi + 25 \\pi = 90 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Surface area of a SPHERE of radius 7 cm in cm^2 to 3 s.f.', answer: 616, tol: 2,
        solution: '4 \\pi \\times 49 = 196 \\pi \\approx 615.75.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L16: Composite solids & word problems ─────────
  {
    id: 'L16',
    title: 'Lesson 16 · Composite solids · word problems',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Add and subtract whole-solid volumes',
      body: [
        'Real solids combine simpler shapes — a rocket is a cylinder with a cone on top; a toy is a hemisphere joined to a cone; a paperweight is a cuboid with a prism cut out.',
        'Strategy: identify each component, find its volume (or surface area), then ADD the components that are present and SUBTRACT the parts that are removed.',
        'WATER DISPLACEMENT trick: a solid object dropped into a cylinder of water raises the water level. The extra volume = volume of solid = \\pi r^2 \\times \\Delta h, where r is the cylinder radius and \\Delta h is the rise.',
        'For PARTIALLY-FILLED containers, compute volume of the empty space the same way you compute volume of the fluid — both are just chunks of the container.',
      ],
      example: 'A rocket is a cylinder of r = 2, h = 10 with a cone of r = 2, h = 3 on top. V = \\pi \\times 4 \\times 10 + \\frac{1}{3} \\pi \\times 4 \\times 3 = 40 \\pi + 4 \\pi = 44 \\pi cm^3.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A toy is a hemisphere of radius 3 cm joined to a cone of base r = 3 cm and h = 4 cm. Volume in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['30 \\pi cm^3', '36 \\pi cm^3', '12 \\pi cm^3', '54 \\pi cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Hem: \\frac{2}{3} \\pi \\times 27 = 18 \\pi. Cone: \\frac{1}{3} \\pi \\times 9 \\times 4 = 12 \\pi. Total 30 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A solid is a cylinder of r = 5 cm and h = 8 cm with a hemisphere of r = 5 cm cut from one end. Volume in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['\\frac{350}{3} \\pi cm^3', '200 \\pi cm^3', '\\frac{250}{3} \\pi cm^3', '300 \\pi cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\pi \\times 25 \\times 8 - \\frac{2}{3} \\pi \\times 125 = 200 \\pi - \\frac{250}{3} \\pi = \\frac{350}{3} \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A metal ball of radius 2 cm is dropped into a cylinder of radius 5 cm partly filled with water. The water rises by how many cm? (3 s.f.)',
        options: ['0.427 cm', '1.07 cm', '0.213 cm', '4.19 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\Delta h = \\frac{V_{ball}}{\\pi r^2} = \\frac{(4/3) \\pi \\times 8}{\\pi \\times 25} = \\frac{32}{75} \\approx 0.427.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A rocket = cylinder (r = 2, h = 10) + cone (r = 2, h = 6) on top. Volume in cm^3 in terms of \\pi?',
        options: ['48 \\pi', '40 \\pi', '64 \\pi', '24 \\pi'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Cyl: 40 \\pi. Cone: \\frac{1}{3} \\pi \\times 4 \\times 6 = 8 \\pi. Total 48 \\pi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A wooden paperweight is a cuboid 8 cm by 6 cm by 4 cm with a triangular prism cut out (cross-section a right triangle of legs 3 cm and 4 cm, length 6 cm). Volume left to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['156 cm^3', '192 cm^3', '108 cm^3', '228 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '8 \\times 6 \\times 4 - \\frac{1}{2} \\times 3 \\times 4 \\times 6 = 192 - 36 = 156.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'The Earth is approximately a sphere of diameter 12 800 km. Approximate volume in km^3 to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['1.10 \\times 10^{12}', '1.10 \\times 10^{11}', '8.78 \\times 10^{11}', '5.36 \\times 10^9'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'r = 6400; V = \\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3 \\approx 1.0986 \\times 10^{12}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cylindrical rainwater tank is 1.5 m tall with diameter 1.4 m. How many litres can it hold (to 3 s.f.)? (1 m^3 = 1000 L)',
        options: ['2 310 L', '925 L', '4 620 L', '1 540 L'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'V = \\pi \\times 0.7^2 \\times 1.5 = 0.735 \\pi \\approx 2.309 m^3 = 2 309 L \\approx 2 310 L.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A cone of radius 3 cm and height 4 cm and a sphere of radius r have the same volume. Find r in cm to 3 s.f.',
        options: ['2.08 cm', '3.00 cm', '1.44 cm', '4.36 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3 = \\frac{1}{3} \\pi \\times 9 \\times 4 = 12 \\pi \\to r^3 = 9 \\to r \\approx 2.08.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A frustum: pyramid of height 6 with square base side 12 cut by a plane parallel to base, removing the top pyramid of height 4 with square base side 8. Volume of FRUSTUM?',
        options: ['203 cm^3', '288 cm^3', '85.3 cm^3', '160 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'V_{whole} = \\frac{1}{3} \\times 144 \\times 6 = 288. V_{upper} = \\frac{1}{3} \\times 64 \\times 4 = 85.33. Frustum = 288 - 85.33 = 202.67.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A glass pyramid ornament has a regular hexagonal base of area 41.57 cm^2 and perpendicular height 20 cm. Volume to 3 s.f.?',
        options: ['277 cm^3', '831 cm^3', '139 cm^3', '415 cm^3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times 41.57 \\times 20 \\approx 277.1.' },
    ],
  },
]

const CH7_PROGRESS_KEY = 'tenali-chapter7-progress'
function ch7_loadProgress() {
  try { return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(CH7_PROGRESS_KEY) || '{}') || {} } catch { return {} }
}
function ch7_saveProgress(p) { try { localStorage.setItem(CH7_PROGRESS_KEY, JSON.stringify(p)) } catch {} }

// --- Custom math renderer for Chapter 7 ----------------------------------
// Beautiful stacked fractions, vertically centred. Same as ch5/ch6.
function Ch7Frac({ num, den }) {
  return (
    <span style={{
      display: 'inline-flex', flexDirection: 'column', alignItems: 'center',
      verticalAlign: 'middle', margin: '0 0.18em', lineHeight: 1.05,
      fontSize: '0.95em',
    }}>
      <span style={{ padding: '0 0.4em 0.05em', borderBottom: '1.6px solid currentColor' }}>{num}</span>
      <span style={{ padding: '0.05em 0.4em 0' }}>{den}</span>
    </span>
  )
}
function ch7_subOps(s) {
  return String(s)
    .replace(/\\times/g, '×').replace(/\\div/g, '÷')
    .replace(/\\approx/g, '≈').replace(/\\to\b/g, '→')
    .replace(/\\le\b/g, '≤').replace(/\\ge\b/g, '≥')
    .replace(/\\cdot/g, '·').replace(/\\pm/g, '±')
    .replace(/\\pi/g, 'π').replace(/\\theta/g, 'θ')
    .replace(/\\sqrt\{([^{}]+)\}/g, '√($1)')
    .replace(/\\sqrt(\d+)/g, '√$1')
    .replace(/\\ell\b/g, 'ℓ')
    .replace(/\\circ/g, '°')
    .replace(/\\u2113/g, 'ℓ')
    .replace(/\\u00b0/g, '°')
    .replace(/\\u2019/g, '’')
    .replace(/\\\$/g, '$').replace(/\\%/g, '%')
}
function ch7RenderMath(text) {
  if (text == null) return null
  const src = ch7_subOps(text)
  const out = []
  let i = 0, buf = ''
  const flush = () => { if (buf) { out.push(buf); buf = '' } }
  while (i < src.length) {
    if (src.startsWith('\\frac{', i)) {
      flush()
      let j = i + 6, depth = 1
      const ns = j
      while (j < src.length) { if (src[j] === '{') depth++; else if (src[j] === '}') { depth--; if (depth === 0) break } j++ }
      const numStr = src.slice(ns, j); j++
      if (src[j] !== '{') { buf += src.slice(i, j); i = j; continue }
      j++; depth = 1
      const ds = j
      while (j < src.length) { if (src[j] === '{') depth++; else if (src[j] === '}') { depth--; if (depth === 0) break } j++ }
      const denStr = src.slice(ds, j); j++
      out.push(<Ch7Frac key={`f${out.length}`} num={ch7RenderMath(numStr)} den={ch7RenderMath(denStr)} />)
      i = j
    } else if (src[i] === '^') {
      const m = src.slice(i).match(/^\^(-?\d+)/)
      if (m) { flush(); out.push(<sup key={`s${out.length}`} style={{ fontSize: '0.72em', verticalAlign: 'super' }}>{m[1]}</sup>); i += m[0].length }
      else { buf += src[i]; i++ }
    } else { buf += src[i]; i++ }
  }
  flush()
  return out
}

const CH7_AUTO_ADVANCE_MS = 5000
// CH7_RETRY_GAP removed: wrong answers now appended to end of playList (see SKILL.md rule #5)

function Chapter7App({ onBack }) {
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState(ch7_loadProgress)
  const [activeId, setActiveId] = useState(null)
  const [phase, setPhase] = useState('teach')
  const [qIdx, setQIdx] = useState(0)
  const [playList, setPlayList] = useState([])
  const [lastWrongSrc, setLastWrongSrc] = useState(null)
  const [selectedIdx, setSelectedIdx] = useState(null)
  const [fillInput, setFillInput] = useState('')
  const [revealed, setRevealed] = useState(false)
  const [isCorrect, setIsCorrect] = useState(false)
  const [autoCountdown, setAutoCountdown] = useState(0)
  const inputRef = useRef(null)
  const autoTimerRef = useRef(null)
  const advanceRef = useRef(() => {})

  const lesson = activeId ? CH7_LESSONS.find(l => l.id === activeId) : null
  const currentSourceIdx = playList[qIdx]
  const currentQ = lesson && currentSourceIdx != null ? lesson.questions[currentSourceIdx] : null
  const isRetry = useMemo(() => {
    if (currentSourceIdx == null) return false
    return playList.slice(0, qIdx).includes(currentSourceIdx)
  }, [playList, qIdx, currentSourceIdx])

  const optionOrder = useMemo(() => {
    if (!currentQ || currentQ.kind !== 'mcq') return []
    return ch7_seededShuffle(currentQ.options.length, `${activeId}-${qIdx}-${currentSourceIdx}-${currentQ.prompt}`)
  }, [activeId, qIdx, currentSourceIdx, currentQ])
  const correctDisplayIdx = useMemo(() => optionOrder.indexOf(currentQ?.correct ?? -1), [optionOrder, currentQ])

  useEffect(() => { ch7_saveProgress(progress) }, [progress])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || revealed) return
    if (currentQ?.kind?.startsWith('fill') && inputRef.current) inputRef.current.focus()
  }, [phase, qIdx, revealed, currentQ])

  const startLesson = (id) => {
    setActiveId(id)
    const lessonRef = CH7_LESSONS.find(l => l.id === id)
    const initial = Array.from({ length: lessonRef.questions.length }, (_, i) => i)
    setPlayList(initial)
    setLastWrongSrc(null)
    const p = progress[id] || {}
    if (p.teachSeen) { setPhase('practice'); setQIdx(p.qIdx || 0) }
    else { setPhase('teach'); setQIdx(0) }
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
  }

  const acknowledgeTeach = () => {
    setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: 0 } }))
    setPhase('practice'); setQIdx(0)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
    setLastWrongSrc(null)
  }

  const submitFill = () => {
    if (!currentQ) return
    if (revealed) { advance(); return }
    const ok = ch7_checkFill(currentQ, fillInput)
    setIsCorrect(ok); setRevealed(true)
    setLastWrongSrc(ok ? null : currentSourceIdx)
  }

  const pickMcq = (displayIdx) => {
    if (!currentQ || revealed || currentQ.kind !== 'mcq') return
    const optSourceIdx = optionOrder[displayIdx]
    const ok = optSourceIdx === currentQ.correct
    setSelectedIdx(displayIdx); setIsCorrect(ok); setRevealed(true)
    setLastWrongSrc(ok ? null : currentSourceIdx)
  }

  const cancelAutoAdvance = () => {
    if (autoTimerRef.current) { clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null }
    setAutoCountdown(0)
  }

  const advance = () => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    if (!lesson) return
    let workingList = playList
    if (lastWrongSrc != null) {
      // Wrong answers go to the END of the lesson — student finishes all
      // fresh questions first, then meets the retry cluster at the tail.
      // Lesson cannot complete until every wrong-answered question has
      // eventually been answered correctly (each wrong attempt re-appends).
      workingList = [...playList, lastWrongSrc]
      setPlayList(workingList)
      setLastWrongSrc(null)
    }
    const next = qIdx + 1
    if (next >= workingList.length) {
      setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: lesson.questions.length, completed: true } }))
      setPhase('done')
    } else {
      setQIdx(next)
      setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
      setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: Math.min(lesson.questions.length, next) } }))
    }
  }
  advanceRef.current = advance

  const jumpToQuestion = (i) => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    if (!lesson) return
    const clamped = Math.max(0, Math.min(playList.length - 1, i))
    setQIdx(clamped); setLastWrongSrc(null)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
    setProgress(p => {
      const cur = p[activeId] || {}
      const saved = Math.max(cur.qIdx || 0, Math.min(lesson.questions.length, clamped))
      return { ...p, [activeId]: { ...cur, teachSeen: true, qIdx: saved } }
    })
  }

  const backToOverview = () => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    setActiveId(null); setPhase('teach'); setQIdx(0)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
  }

  const resetAll = () => {
    if (!confirm('Reset all Chapter 7 progress?')) return
    setProgress({}); ch7_saveProgress({})
    backToOverview()
  }

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || !revealed) { cancelAutoAdvance(); return }
    const total = Math.round(CH7_AUTO_ADVANCE_MS / 1000)
    setAutoCountdown(total)
    autoTimerRef.current = setInterval(() => {
      setAutoCountdown(prev => {
        if (prev <= 1) {
          clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null
          advanceRef.current()
          return 0
        }
        return prev - 1
      })
    }, 1000)
    return () => { if (autoTimerRef.current) { clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null } }
  }, [phase, revealed, qIdx, activeId])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || !currentQ) return
    const onKey = (e) => {
      if (revealed) {
        if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') { e.preventDefault(); advance() }
        return
      }
      if (currentQ.kind === 'mcq') {
        const k = e.key
        if (/^[1-9]$/.test(k)) {
          const i = parseInt(k, 10) - 1
          if (i < currentQ.options.length) { e.preventDefault(); pickMcq(i) }
        }
      } else if (currentQ.kind?.startsWith('fill')) {
        if (e.key === 'Enter') { e.preventDefault(); submitFill() }
      }
    }
    window.addEventListener('keydown', onKey)
    return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', onKey)
  }, [phase, qIdx, revealed, currentQ, fillInput, optionOrder])

  // ────────── Overview ──────────
  if (!activeId) {
    const total = CH7_LESSONS.length
    const done = CH7_LESSONS.filter(l => progress[l.id]?.completed).length
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 760, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, alignItems: 'center', marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={onBack}>← Home</button>
          <button className="back-button" style={{ marginLeft: 'auto' }} onClick={resetAll}>Reset progress</button>
        </div>
        <h1 style={{ marginBottom: 4 }}>Chapter 7 — Perimeter, Area & Volume</h1>
        <p className="subtitle" style={{ marginTop: 0 }}>
          Cambridge IGCSE Mathematics · {done}/{total} lessons complete
        </p>
        <p style={{ opacity: 0.85, marginTop: 8 }}>
          Pick the next lesson. Each one starts with a short explanation, then a stream of multiple-choice and fill-in-the-blank
          questions — easy warm-ups first, then the actual chapter exercise problems.
        </p>
        <ol style={{ listStyle: 'none', padding: 0, marginTop: 16 }}>
          {CH7_LESSONS.map((l) => {
            const p = progress[l.id] || {}
            const completed = p.completed
            const inProg = !completed && (p.teachSeen || (p.qIdx || 0) > 0)
            return (
              <li key={l.id} style={{ marginBottom: 8 }}>
                <button
                  onClick={() => startLesson(l.id)}
                  style={{
                    width: '100%', textAlign: 'left', padding: '12px 14px',
                    borderRadius: 10,
                    borderLeft: completed ? '4px solid #2ea043' : inProg ? '4px solid #388bfd' : '1px solid var(--clr-border, #444)',
                    borderTop: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    borderRight: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    borderBottom: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    background: completed
                      ? 'linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(46,160,67,0.32) 0%, rgba(46,160,67,0.18) 100%)'
                      : inProg ? 'rgba(56,139,253,0.10)' : 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
                    color: 'var(--clr-text)',
                    fontWeight: completed ? 600 : 400,
                    cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem',
                    boxShadow: completed ? '0 0 0 1px rgba(46,160,67,0.35) inset' : 'none',
                  }}
                >
                  <span style={{ marginRight: 8 }}>{completed ? '✅' : inProg ? '▶' : '○'}</span>
                  {ch7RenderMath(l.title)}
                  {completed && (
                    <span style={{
                      float: 'right', fontSize: '0.72rem', fontWeight: 700, letterSpacing: '0.5px',
                      color: '#fff', background: '#2ea043', padding: '2px 8px', borderRadius: 10,
                    }}>DONE</span>
                  )}
                  {p.qIdx > 0 && !completed && (
                    <span style={{ float: 'right', fontSize: '0.8rem', opacity: 0.7 }}>{p.qIdx}/{l.questions.length}</span>
                  )}
                </button>
              </li>
            )
          })}
        </ol>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Teach ──────────
  if (phase === 'teach') {
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        </div>
        <h2 style={{ marginBottom: 4 }}>{ch7RenderMath(lesson.title)}</h2>
        <h3 style={{ color: 'var(--clr-accent, #6cf)', marginTop: 16 }}>{ch7RenderMath(lesson.teach.heading)}</h3>
        {lesson.teach.body.map((para, i) => (
          <p key={i} style={{ lineHeight: 1.7, marginBottom: 10, fontSize: '1rem' }}>{ch7RenderMath(para)}</p>
        ))}
        <div style={{
          marginTop: 14, padding: 14, borderRadius: 8,
          background: 'rgba(108,206,255,0.08)', border: '1px solid rgba(108,206,255,0.25)',
          fontSize: '1rem', lineHeight: 1.7,
        }}>
          <strong>Worked example: </strong>{ch7RenderMath(lesson.teach.example)}
        </div>
        {lesson.qFormat && <p style={{ marginTop: 14, fontSize: '0.9rem', opacity: 0.8 }}><em>Note:</em> {lesson.qFormat}</p>}
        <button onClick={acknowledgeTeach} style={{
          marginTop: 18, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8, fontSize: '1rem',
          background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)', color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer',
        }}>I've got it — start questions →</button>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Done ──────────
  if (phase === 'done') {
    const idx = CH7_LESSONS.findIndex(l => l.id === activeId)
    const next = CH7_LESSONS[idx + 1]
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        </div>
        <h2>🎉 Lesson complete</h2>
        <p>You finished <strong>{ch7RenderMath(lesson.title)}</strong>.</p>
        {next ? (
          <button onClick={() => startLesson(next.id)} style={{
            marginTop: 12, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8, fontSize: '1rem',
            background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)', color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer',
          }}>Next: {ch7RenderMath(next.title)} →</button>
        ) : (
          <p style={{ marginTop: 16, fontSize: '1.05rem' }}>🎓 You've completed every lesson in Chapter 7.</p>
        )}
        <button onClick={backToOverview} style={{
          marginTop: 12, marginLeft: 8, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8,
          background: 'transparent', color: 'var(--clr-text)', border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', cursor: 'pointer',
        }}>Back to lessons</button>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Practice ──────────
  const sliderMax = Math.max(1, playList.length)
  return (
    <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
      <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 12, alignItems: 'center' }}>
        <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        <button className="back-button" onClick={() => setPhase('teach')}>📖 Re-read teach</button>
        <span style={{ marginLeft: 'auto', fontSize: '0.85rem', opacity: 0.75 }}>
          Question {qIdx + 1} / {sliderMax}
          {sliderMax > lesson.questions.length && (
            <span style={{ marginLeft: 6, color: '#f0a020' }}>· {sliderMax - lesson.questions.length} retry queued</span>
          )}
        </span>
      </div>
      <h3 style={{ marginBottom: 8 }}>{ch7RenderMath(lesson.title)}</h3>
      <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 12, marginBottom: 18 }}>
        <span style={{ fontSize: '0.78rem', opacity: 0.65, minWidth: 18, textAlign: 'right' }}>1</span>
        <input
          type="range"
          min={1}
          max={sliderMax}
          value={qIdx + 1}
          onChange={e => jumpToQuestion(parseInt(e.target.value, 10) - 1)}
          aria-label="Jump to question"
          style={{
            flex: 1, accentColor: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
            cursor: 'pointer', height: 22,
          }}
        />
        <span style={{ fontSize: '0.78rem', opacity: 0.65, minWidth: 22 }}>{sliderMax}</span>
      </div>

      <div style={{
        padding: '22px 24px', borderRadius: 10, background: 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
        border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #333)', marginBottom: 16,
        fontSize: '1.25rem', lineHeight: 2.1, textAlign: 'center',
        display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center', minHeight: 80,
        position: 'relative',
      }}>
        {isRetry && (
          <span style={{
            position: 'absolute', top: 8, right: 12, fontSize: '0.7rem', fontWeight: 700,
            letterSpacing: '0.5px', color: '#f0a020', background: 'rgba(240,160,32,0.15)',
            border: '1px solid rgba(240,160,32,0.45)', padding: '2px 8px', borderRadius: 10,
          }}>↻ RETRY</span>
        )}
        <span>{ch7RenderMath(currentQ.prompt)}</span>
      </div>

      {currentQ.kind === 'mcq' ? (
        <div className="options-list">
          {optionOrder.map((srcIdx, displayIdx) => {
            const opt = currentQ.options[srcIdx]
            const isSelected = selectedIdx === displayIdx
            const isCorrectOpt = revealed && correctDisplayIdx === displayIdx
            const isWrongPick = revealed && isSelected && !isCorrect
            return (
              <button
                key={displayIdx}
                className={`option-card ${isSelected ? 'selected' : ''} ${isCorrectOpt ? 'correct-option' : ''} ${isWrongPick ? 'wrong-option' : ''}`}
                onClick={() => pickMcq(displayIdx)}
                disabled={revealed}
                style={{
                  borderColor: isCorrectOpt ? 'var(--clr-correct, #2ea043)' : isWrongPick ? 'var(--clr-wrong, #f85149)' : undefined,
                  background: isCorrectOpt ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.15)' : isWrongPick ? 'rgba(248,81,73,0.15)' : undefined,
                  display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center',
                  position: 'relative', padding: '18px 24px', minHeight: 64,
                  fontSize: '1.1rem', lineHeight: 1.9,
                }}
              >
                <span style={{
                  position: 'absolute', left: 18, top: '50%', transform: 'translateY(-50%)',
                  fontWeight: 700, opacity: 0.6, fontSize: '0.95rem',
                }}>{CH7_OPTION_LABEL[displayIdx]}.</span>
                <span style={{ display: 'inline-flex', alignItems: 'center' }}>{ch7RenderMath(opt)}</span>
              </button>
            )
          })}
        </div>
      ) : (
        <>
          <input
            ref={inputRef}
            type="text"
            value={fillInput}
            onChange={e => setFillInput(e.target.value)}
            disabled={revealed}
            placeholder="Your answer…"
            autoComplete="off"
            style={{
              width: '100%', padding: '14px 16px', fontSize: '1.15rem', borderRadius: 8,
              border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', textAlign: 'center',
              background: revealed ? 'rgba(255,255,255,0.04)' : 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
              color: 'var(--clr-text)', boxSizing: 'border-box',
            }}
          />
          {!revealed && (
            <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginTop: 12, justifyContent: 'center' }}>
              <button onClick={submitFill} disabled={!fillInput.trim()} style={{
                padding: '10px 22px', borderRadius: 6, background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
                color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem',
                opacity: fillInput.trim() ? 1 : 0.5,
              }}>Check</button>
            </div>
          )}
        </>
      )}

      {revealed && (
        <>
          <div style={{
            marginTop: 16, padding: 16, borderRadius: 8,
            background: isCorrect ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.15)' : 'rgba(248,81,73,0.15)',
            border: `1px solid ${isCorrect ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.45)' : 'rgba(248,81,73,0.45)'}`,
            fontSize: '1rem', lineHeight: 1.9,
          }}>
            <strong>{isCorrect ? '✅ Correct!' : '❌ Not quite.'}</strong>
            <div style={{ marginTop: 8, display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: 6 }}>
              <strong>Answer:</strong>
              <span>{currentQ.kind === 'mcq'
                ? ch7RenderMath(currentQ.options[currentQ.correct])
                : ch7RenderMath(String(currentQ.answer))}</span>
            </div>
            {currentQ.solution && (
              <div style={{ marginTop: 8, opacity: 0.9, display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: 6 }}>
                <strong>Working:</strong>
                <span>{ch7RenderMath(currentQ.solution)}</span>
              </div>
            )}
          </div>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 12, marginTop: 14, justifyContent: 'center' }}>
            <button onClick={advance} style={{
              padding: '12px 28px', borderRadius: 8, background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
              color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '1rem', fontWeight: 600,
            }}>
              {qIdx + 1 === lesson.questions.length ? 'Finish lesson →' : 'Next →'}
            </button>
            <span style={{ fontSize: '0.85rem', opacity: 0.65 }}>
              auto-advance in {autoCountdown}s · or press <kbd style={{ padding: '1px 6px', border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', borderRadius: 4, fontSize: '0.78rem' }}>Enter</kbd>
            </span>
          </div>
        </>
      )}
    </div>
  )
}

/* =====================================================================
 *  Chapter8App — Cambridge IGCSE Chapter 8 (Introduction to Probability)
 *
 *  Mounted at /chapter8. Same UX as Chapter5App / Chapter6App / Chapter7App:
 *  ordered chain of lessons, every one unlocked from the start, slider to
 *  jump questions, MCQ with 1-9 keys + fill-in fallbacks, 5s auto-advance,
 *  completed lessons go green, wrong answers re-queued after a gap.
 *  See Tenali/skills/igcse-chapter/SKILL.md for the full pattern.
 * ===================================================================== */

const CH8_OPTION_LABEL = ['1','2','3','4','5','6','7','8','9']

function ch8_seededShuffle(n, key) {
  let h = 2166136261
  for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) { h ^= key.charCodeAt(i); h = Math.imul(h, 16777619) }
  const rand = () => { h = Math.imul(h ^ (h >>> 15), 2246822507); h = Math.imul(h ^ (h >>> 13), 3266489909); return ((h ^= h >>> 16) >>> 0) / 4294967295 }
  const arr = Array.from({ length: n }, (_, i) => i)
  for (let i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) { const j = Math.floor(rand() * (i + 1)); [arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]] }
  return arr
}

function ch8_gcd(a, b) { a = Math.abs(a); b = Math.abs(b); while (b) { [a, b] = [b, a % b] } return a || 1 }
function ch8_reduce(n, d) {
  if (d === 0) return null
  if (d < 0) { n = -n; d = -d }
  const g = ch8_gcd(n, d)
  return { n: n / g, d: d / g }
}
function ch8_parseFrac(raw) {
  if (raw == null) return null
  let s = String(raw).trim().replace(/\\frac\{(-?\d+)\}\{(-?\d+)\}/g, '$1/$2').replace(/\s+/g, ' ').replace(/–/g, '-')
  if (!s) return null
  const mixed = s.match(/^(-?)(\d+)\s+(\d+)\s*\/\s*(\d+)$/)
  if (mixed) {
    const sign = mixed[1] === '-' ? -1 : 1
    const w = +mixed[2], n = +mixed[3], d = +mixed[4]
    if (d === 0) return null
    return ch8_reduce(sign * (w * d + n), d)
  }
  const frac = s.match(/^(-?\d+)\s*\/\s*(-?\d+)$/)
  if (frac) {
    const n = +frac[1], d = +frac[2]
    if (d === 0) return null
    return ch8_reduce(n, d)
  }
  const num = Number(s)
  if (Number.isFinite(num)) {
    if (Number.isInteger(num)) return { n: num, d: 1 }
    const sign = num < 0 ? -1 : 1
    const decimals = (s.split('.')[1] || '').length
    const denom = Math.pow(10, decimals)
    return ch8_reduce(sign * Math.round(Math.abs(num) * denom), denom)
  }
  return null
}
function ch8_fracEqual(a, b) { return a && b && a.n === b.n && a.d === b.d }
function ch8_normalizeNumStr(s) {
  return String(s).trim().replace(/[$,\s%]/g, '').replace(/–/g, '-')
}
function ch8_numEqual(user, expected, tol) {
  const u = parseFloat(ch8_normalizeNumStr(user))
  if (!Number.isFinite(u)) return false
  const t = tol != null ? tol : Math.max(0.005, Math.abs(expected) * 0.005)
  return Math.abs(u - expected) <= t
}

function ch8_checkFill(q, raw) {
  if (!raw || !raw.trim()) return false
  switch (q.kind) {
    case 'fill-num': return ch8_numEqual(raw, q.answer, q.tol)
    case 'fill-frac': {
      const u = ch8_parseFrac(raw)
      const e = ch8_parseFrac(q.answer)
      return ch8_fracEqual(u, e)
    }
    case 'fill-text': return raw.trim().toLowerCase() === String(q.answer).trim().toLowerCase()
    default: return false
  }
}

// --- Lesson catalogue ---------------------------------------------------
// Cambridge IGCSE Chapter 8 — Introduction to Probability
// Sections covered: 8.1 Understanding basic probability (vocabulary,
// theoretical/experimental probability, complement); 8.2 Sample space
// diagrams; 8.3 Combining independent and mutually exclusive events.
// See uploads PDF p. 240-257.
const CH8_LESSONS = [
  // ───────────────────── L1: Vocabulary & the 0-1 scale ────────────────
  {
    id: 'L1',
    title: 'Lesson 1 · Probability vocabulary & the 0–1 scale',
    teach: {
      heading: 'How likely is it? — measuring chance',
      body: [
        'PROBABILITY is a measure of how likely an event is to happen. It is always a number between 0 and 1 (inclusive).',
        'P = 0 means the event is IMPOSSIBLE. P = 1 means it is CERTAIN. P = \\frac{1}{2} means equally likely to happen or not.',
        'The set of all possible OUTCOMES of an experiment is called the SAMPLE SPACE. An EVENT is one or more of those outcomes.',
        'Probabilities can be written as fractions (\\frac{3}{4}), decimals (0.75), or percentages (75%) — all three describe the same chance.',
        'Useful informal scale: very unlikely (close to 0), unlikely (~0.25), even chance (0.5), likely (~0.75), almost certain (close to 1).',
      ],
      example: 'Tossing a fair coin: sample space = {H, T}. Event "heads" has probability \\frac{1}{2} = 0.5 = 50%.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Which value CANNOT be a probability?',
        options: ['1.2', '0', '0.5', '\\frac{3}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Probability is between 0 and 1 inclusive. 1.2 > 1 so it is impossible.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag contains only red balls. The probability of picking a blue ball is …',
        options: ['0', '1', '\\frac{1}{2}', '0.5'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'There are no blue balls, so the event is IMPOSSIBLE.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A coin is tossed. Probability of getting heads OR tails is …',
        options: ['1', '\\frac{1}{2}', '0', '2'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'One of those two outcomes is CERTAIN to happen.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A probability of \\frac{1}{2} means the event is …',
        options: ['equally likely to happen as not', 'certain', 'impossible', 'almost impossible'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{2} = 0.5 — even chance.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Which of these probabilities is the LARGEST?',
        options: ['0.6', '\\frac{1}{2}', '40%', '\\frac{3}{10}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.6 = 60%; \\frac{1}{2} = 50%; 40% = 0.4; \\frac{3}{10} = 0.3.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A probability of 0.95 best describes an event that is …',
        options: ['almost certain', 'impossible', 'very unlikely', 'an even chance'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.95 is very close to 1 (certain).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A spinner has equal sectors numbered 1, 2, 3, 4. The sample space when you spin it once is …',
        options: ['{1, 2, 3, 4}', '{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}', '4', '{H, T}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sample space is the SET of all possible outcomes.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A standard die is rolled. Which is an EVENT?',
        options: ['"the score is greater than 4"', '6', '"the die"', 'the sample space'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'An event is a description of one or more outcomes — here it picks {5, 6}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Express \\frac{4}{5} as a percentage.',
        options: ['80%', '4.5%', '20%', '54%'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{5} = \\frac{80}{100} = 80%.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Express 0.32 as a fraction in simplest form.',
        options: ['\\frac{8}{25}', '\\frac{32}{100}', '\\frac{16}{50}', '\\frac{1}{32}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.32 = \\frac{32}{100} = \\frac{8}{25}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L2: Theoretical probability ───────────────────
  {
    id: 'L2',
    title: 'Lesson 2 · Theoretical probability (favourable / total)',
    teach: {
      heading: 'P(event) = \\frac{number of favourable outcomes}{total number of outcomes}',
      body: [
        'When every outcome of an experiment is equally likely (a fair coin, a fair die, a well-shuffled deck), we can calculate the THEORETICAL probability of an event by counting.',
        'P(event) = \\frac{number of favourable outcomes}{total number of equally likely outcomes}.',
        'A "favourable" outcome is one for which the event happens. A "total" outcome is any element of the sample space.',
        'Always simplify the fraction at the end.',
        'Tip: when the question says "fair", "unbiased", or "random", the outcomes are equally likely and you can apply this formula directly.',
      ],
      example: 'A fair die rolled once. P(score is even) = \\frac{3}{6} = \\frac{1}{2} (favourable: 2, 4, 6; total: 6).',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Roll a fair six-sided die. P(rolling a 3)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 favourable (the face "3") out of 6 equally likely.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Roll a fair six-sided die. P(rolling an even number)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{3}{6} = \\frac{1}{2} (favourable: 2, 4, 6).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Roll a fair six-sided die. P(rolling a prime)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Primes are 2, 3, 5; that is 3 out of 6 = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 12 numbered discs (1 to 12). One is drawn at random. P(disc shows a 7)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{7}{12}', '\\frac{1}{7}', '\\frac{1}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'One favourable disc out of 12.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: '12 discs numbered 1 to 12. P(disc shows an even number)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{6}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Evens 2,4,6,8,10,12 — that is 6 out of 12 = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: '12 discs numbered 1 to 12. P(disc shows a prime)?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{12}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{6}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Primes \\le 12 are 2, 3, 5, 7, 11 — five primes out of 12.' },
      { kind: 'fill-frac', prompt: 'Roll a fair die. P(scoring at least 5) — give as a simplified fraction.', answer: '1/3',
        solution: '\\{5, 6\\} \\to \\frac{2}{6} = \\frac{1}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'fill-frac', prompt: 'A spinner has 8 equal sectors numbered 1–8. P(landing on a number greater than 5)? Simplified fraction.', answer: '3/8',
        solution: '\\{6, 7, 8\\} = 3 out of 8.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A spinner has 8 equal sectors numbered 1–8. P(landing on a multiple of 3)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{8}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{8}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Multiples of 3 in 1–8: \\{3, 6\\} = 2 out of 8 = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 20 balls: 5 red, 7 blue, 8 green. P(picking a red ball)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{5}{15}', '\\frac{7}{20}', '\\frac{8}{20}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{5}{20} = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same bag (5 R, 7 B, 8 G). P(picking either red OR blue)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{5}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{12}{20}', '\\frac{1}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{12}{20} = \\frac{3}{5} (count red + blue out of total).' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L3: Experimental probability & RF ─────────────
  {
    id: 'L3',
    title: 'Lesson 3 · Experimental probability & relative frequency',
    teach: {
      heading: 'P(event) \\approx \\frac{number of times it happened}{number of trials}',
      body: [
        'Theoretical probability requires equally likely outcomes. When you do not know whether outcomes are equally likely (e.g. a possibly biased coin, a real-world question), you can run an EXPERIMENT and use the result.',
        'EXPERIMENTAL probability (also called RELATIVE FREQUENCY) = \\frac{number of times the event happens}{number of trials}.',
        'The MORE TRIALS you run, the closer the experimental probability tends to get to the true (theoretical) probability — this is sometimes called the "law of large numbers".',
        'EXPECTED occurrences: if you do N trials and the probability is p, you EXPECT about N \\times p of them to be successes. (E.g. 200 coin tosses \\to expect about 100 heads.)',
        'If the experimental probability is very different from the theoretical one over MANY trials, suspect BIAS (e.g. a weighted die).',
      ],
      example: 'A drawing pin is tossed 80 times and lands point-up 36 times. Experimental P(point-up) = \\frac{36}{80} = \\frac{9}{20} = 0.45.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A six-sided die is rolled 100 times; the score 5 appears 14 times. Experimental P(rolling a 5)?',
        options: ['\\frac{14}{100}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{14}{6}', '\\frac{86}{100}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{14}{100} = \\frac{7}{50} = 0.14.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same die. Express the experimental P(rolling a 5) as a percentage.',
        options: ['14%', '7%', '50%', '20%'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{14}{100} = 14%.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A coin is tossed 200 times and shows heads 80 times. Experimental P(heads) as a decimal?',
        options: ['0.4', '0.5', '0.8', '0.04'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{80}{200} = 0.4.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In 200 tosses, this coin gave heads 80 times. Is it likely to be FAIR?',
        options: ['No — the experimental P is far from 0.5, so probably biased', 'Yes — close to 0.5', 'Cannot tell', 'Yes — 80 is close to 200'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.4 vs theoretical 0.5 over 200 trials is a big gap; likely biased.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A 4-sided spinner is spun 200 times; the score "1" appears 30 times. Experimental P(scoring 1)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{20}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{30}{200}', 'Both A and C'], correct: 3,
        solution: '\\frac{30}{200} = \\frac{3}{20} = 0.15. Both A and C are correct.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'You expect about how many heads in 1000 tosses of a fair coin?',
        options: ['500', '100', '1000', '250'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1000 \\times 0.5 = 500.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag of seeds germinates with probability 0.85. If 200 seeds are sown, expected germinations?',
        options: ['170', '85', '15', '100'], correct: 0,
        solution: '200 \\times 0.85 = 170.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A village has 480 people. A survey says 25% prefer adventure films. Estimated number who do?',
        options: ['120', '60', '240', '25'], correct: 0,
        solution: '480 \\times 0.25 = 120.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In a town of 25 000 people, the experimental probability of being right-handed is 0.88. Expected number of right-handers?',
        options: ['22 000', '3 000', '2 200', '12 500'], correct: 0,
        solution: '25 000 \\times 0.88 = 22 000.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'A drawing pin is tossed 200 times and lands point-up 120 times. Experimental P(point-up) as a decimal.', answer: 0.6, tol: 0.01,
        solution: '\\frac{120}{200} = 0.6.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L4: The complement (NOT happening) ────────────
  {
    id: 'L4',
    title: 'Lesson 4 · The complement: P(A\\u2032) = 1 \\u2013 P(A)',
    teach: {
      heading: 'If A happens with probability p, then NOT A happens with 1 \\u2013 p',
      body: [
        'For any event A, the COMPLEMENT (also written A\\u2032 or "not A") is the event that A does NOT happen.',
        'Because every trial either has A or has not-A, P(A) + P(A\\u2032) = 1, so P(A\\u2032) = 1 \\u2013 P(A).',
        'This is one of the most useful ideas in probability — when the "event happens" case is hard to count, the "event does NOT happen" case is often easier.',
        'Examples: P(rain tomorrow) = 0.3 \\to P(no rain) = 0.7. P(passing a test) = \\frac{2}{3} \\to P(failing) = \\frac{1}{3}.',
        'Idiom: "at LEAST one" is often easier as 1 \\u2013 P(NONE).',
      ],
      example: 'P(Jas drives well) = \\frac{2}{3}. P(Jas does not drive well) = 1 \\u2013 \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{1}{3}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(rain tomorrow) = 0.4. P(no rain tomorrow) = ?',
        options: ['0.6', '0.4', '0.5', '0'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 0.4 = 0.6.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(passing the driving test) = \\frac{3}{4}. P(failing) = ?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{4}', '0', '\\frac{4}{3}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{3}{4} = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a red ball) = \\frac{2}{7}. P(NOT red) = ?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{7}', '\\frac{2}{7}', '\\frac{7}{2}', '\\frac{1}{7}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{2}{7} = \\frac{5}{7}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(scoring 6 on a die) = \\frac{1}{6}. P(NOT scoring 6) = ?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{6}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{6}{5}', '0'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{5}{6}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(NOT picking a king from a standard deck) = ?',
        options: ['\\frac{12}{13}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{4}{52}', '\\frac{48}{52}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '4 kings out of 52 \\to P(king) = \\frac{1}{13} \\to P(not king) = \\frac{12}{13}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(an event A) = 30%. P(A\\u2032) = ?',
        options: ['70%', '30%', '0.3', '60%'], correct: 0,
        solution: '100% \\u2013 30% = 70%.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'P(A) = 0.62. P(A\\u2032) as a decimal?', answer: 0.38, tol: 0.001,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 0.62 = 0.38.' },
      { kind: 'fill-frac', prompt: 'P(A) = \\frac{3}{8}. P(A\\u2032) as a simplified fraction?', answer: '5/8',
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{3}{8} = \\frac{5}{8}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A spinner has P(red) = \\frac{1}{4}, P(blue) = \\frac{1}{4}. P(NEITHER red nor blue) = ?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{4}', '0'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'P(red OR blue) = \\frac{1}{2}, so P(neither) = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(an event A) = 1. P(A\\u2032) = ?',
        options: ['0', '1', '0.5', 'Cannot say'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'A is CERTAIN, so its complement is IMPOSSIBLE.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L5: Probability with playing cards ────────────
  {
    id: 'L5',
    title: 'Lesson 5 · Probability with playing cards',
    teach: {
      heading: 'A standard deck has 52 cards in 4 suits',
      body: [
        'A standard pack has 52 cards in four SUITS: hearts (\\u2665), diamonds (\\u2666), clubs (\\u2663), spades (\\u2660). Hearts and diamonds are RED; clubs and spades are BLACK.',
        'Each suit has 13 cards: ace, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, jack, queen, king. So there are 4 aces, 4 kings, 4 sevens, 13 hearts, 26 red cards, etc.',
        'Picking a single card at random from a well-shuffled deck makes every card equally likely, so P(event) = \\frac{number of cards in the event}{52}.',
        'JACK / QUEEN / KING are called "court" or "face" cards — there are 12 of them altogether (3 per suit \\times 4 suits).',
      ],
      example: 'P(picking a heart) = \\frac{13}{52} = \\frac{1}{4}. P(picking the king of hearts) = \\frac{1}{52}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a king from a standard deck)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{52}', '\\frac{4}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{52} = \\frac{1}{13}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a red card)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{13}{52}', '\\frac{26}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Hearts + diamonds = 26 out of 52.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a spade)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{13}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'One suit out of four: \\frac{13}{52} = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a face card — jack, queen, or king)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{13}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{12}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '12 face cards / 52 = \\frac{3}{13}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking the queen of hearts)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{52}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{4}{52}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'There is exactly one such card.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a black card OR a queen)?',
        options: ['\\frac{7}{13}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{15}{52}', '\\frac{1}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '26 black + 4 queens \\u2013 2 black queens (counted twice) = 28 \\to \\frac{28}{52} = \\frac{7}{13}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking an ace OR a king)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{13}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{8}{52}', 'A and C are both right'], correct: 3,
        solution: '4 + 4 = 8 cards out of 52 = \\frac{2}{13}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(NOT picking a heart)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{4}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{13}{52}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{1}{4} = \\frac{3}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(picking a card numbered between 2 and 10 inclusive — counting numbers only)?',
        options: ['\\frac{9}{13}', '\\frac{8}{13}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{4}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '9 ranks (2–10) \\times 4 suits = 36 / 52 = \\frac{9}{13}.' },
      { kind: 'fill-frac', prompt: 'P(picking a prime-numbered card from 2 to 10) — primes are 2, 3, 5, 7. As simplified fraction.', answer: '4/13',
        solution: '4 ranks (2, 3, 5, 7) \\times 4 suits = 16 / 52 = \\frac{4}{13}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L6: Bags, balls, spinners ────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L6',
    title: 'Lesson 6 · Probability with bags, balls & spinners',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Same idea — count the favourable outcomes',
      body: [
        'A bag of identical balls (with different colours) is the workhorse of probability questions. If the balls are identical apart from colour and the draw is RANDOM, every ball is equally likely.',
        'P(a particular colour) = \\frac{number of balls of that colour}{total number of balls}.',
        'A SPINNER with EQUAL sectors is just like a die — each sector is equally likely. If the sectors are NOT equal (e.g. a pie chart with mismatched slices), use the AREA fraction instead.',
        'Watch for "WITHOUT REPLACEMENT" — once a ball is drawn it is removed, so the second draw has fewer balls. This changes the second probability. We will treat this carefully later; for now most questions are with replacement (or only one draw).',
      ],
      example: 'A bag has 5 red, 4 white, 6 blue balls (15 total). P(red) = \\frac{5}{15} = \\frac{1}{3}; P(NOT blue) = \\frac{9}{15} = \\frac{3}{5}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 4 red, 6 blue, 2 green balls (12 total). P(red)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{4}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{12} = \\frac{1}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same bag (4 R, 6 B, 2 G). P(blue OR green)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{8}{12} = \\frac{2}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same bag. P(NOT red)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{4}{12}', '\\frac{3}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{8}{12} = \\frac{2}{3}, the complement of P(red) = \\frac{1}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 12 coloured balls. 4 are blue and the rest are red. P(picking a red one)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{4}{12}', '\\frac{1}{2}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Reds = 12 \\u2013 4 = 8. \\frac{8}{12} = \\frac{2}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Bag has 20 socks: 8 white, 4 grey, 6 red, 2 green. One sock drawn at random. P(green)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{10}', '\\frac{1}{20}', '\\frac{1}{5}', '\\frac{2}{20}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{2}{20} = \\frac{1}{10}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A spinner has 8 EQUAL sectors numbered 1–8. P(landing on a factor of 8)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{8}', '\\frac{1}{8}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Factors of 8 in \\{1..8\\}: 1, 2, 4, 8 — four of them. \\frac{4}{8} = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A spinner has 8 EQUAL sectors 1–8. P(odd number)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{8}', '\\frac{5}{8}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\{1, 3, 5, 7\\} \\to \\frac{4}{8} = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 9 letter tiles spelling "HOLLYWOOD". P(picking the letter "O")?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{2}{9}', '\\frac{4}{9}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'There are 3 Os in HOLLYWOOD: \\frac{3}{9} = \\frac{1}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'HOLLYWOOD letters again. P(picking "H" OR "L")?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{2}{9}', '\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{1}{2}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 H + 2 Ls = 3 / 9 = \\frac{1}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'HOLLYWOOD letters. P(picking "Z")?',
        options: ['0', '\\frac{1}{9}', '1', '\\frac{1}{26}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'No Zs in HOLLYWOOD; impossible event.' },
      { kind: 'fill-frac', prompt: 'A bag has 12 balls: 5 red, 4 white, 3 blue. P(picking white) as simplified fraction.', answer: '1/3',
        solution: '\\frac{4}{12} = \\frac{1}{3}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L7: Sample space diagrams (two events) ────────
  {
    id: 'L7',
    title: 'Lesson 7 · Sample space diagrams (two events)',
    teach: {
      heading: 'A grid of all possible outcomes',
      body: [
        'When two things happen together (two coins, a coin and a die, two dice…), the SAMPLE SPACE has many entries. A SAMPLE SPACE DIAGRAM (a 2-D table) lists every combination so you can count without missing any.',
        'For two coins: rows = first coin (H, T), columns = second coin (H, T). 4 cells, 4 equally likely outcomes.',
        'For two dice: rows = first die 1–6, columns = second die 1–6. 36 cells, each equally likely.',
        'Inside each cell you write the OUTCOME (the pair, or the SUM, or the PRODUCT — whatever the question is about). Then count the cells that match the event you want.',
        'P(event) = \\frac{cells matching the event}{total cells}.',
      ],
      example: 'Two coins. Sample space = \\{HH, HT, TH, TT\\}. P(at least one head) = \\frac{3}{4}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A coin tossed twice. Total number of outcomes in the sample space?',
        options: ['4', '2', '6', '8'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'HH, HT, TH, TT.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two coins tossed. P(both heads)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{3}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'One favourable (HH) out of 4.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two coins tossed. P(at LEAST one head)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '1'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Favourable: HH, HT, TH = 3 out of 4. (Or use 1 \\u2013 P(no heads) = 1 \\u2013 \\frac{1}{4}.)' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two coins tossed. P(no heads)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{3}{4}', '0'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'TT is the only outcome with no heads.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two coins tossed. P(exactly one head)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{4}', '\\frac{1}{3}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'HT and TH \\to \\frac{2}{4} = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A coin and a six-sided die. Total outcomes?',
        options: ['12', '8', '6', '36'], correct: 0,
        solution: '2 \\times 6 = 12.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Coin + die. P(heads AND a 6)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{2}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'One favourable cell (H, 6) out of 12.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. Total cells in the sample space?',
        options: ['36', '12', '6', '11'], correct: 0,
        solution: '6 \\times 6 = 36.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(both show the same number)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{1}{2}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Six "doubles" (1,1) … (6,6) out of 36 = \\frac{1}{6}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(both numbers are different)?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{6}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{30}{30}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 P(same) = 1 \\u2013 \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{5}{6}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L8: Two-dice sums and products ────────────────
  {
    id: 'L8',
    title: 'Lesson 8 · Two-dice sums & products',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Read the table you would draw',
      body: [
        'For two dice, draw a 6-by-6 grid and fill it with the SUM (or the PRODUCT, or the difference) of the two faces. Then count cells.',
        'SUMS run from 2 (1+1) to 12 (6+6). The most likely sum is 7 (six cells: 1+6, 2+5, 3+4, 4+3, 5+2, 6+1). The least likely sums are 2 and 12 (one cell each).',
        'PRODUCTS go from 1 to 36 — but the same product can appear in many cells, and many products in 1–36 do NOT appear at all.',
        'Tip: when the question asks for "less than 5", count cells with sum 2, 3, or 4 — it is easy to forget the boundary.',
      ],
      example: 'Two dice, sum recorded. P(sum = 7) = \\frac{6}{36} = \\frac{1}{6}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum = 7)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{7}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '6 / 36 = \\frac{1}{6}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum = 2)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{18}', '\\frac{2}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Only (1, 1) gives sum 2.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum = 12)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{2}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Only (6, 6).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum less than 5)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{5}{36}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{3}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sums 2, 3, 4 \\to (1,1), (1,2), (2,1), (1,3), (3,1), (2,2). 6 cells / 36 = \\frac{1}{6}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum at least 8)?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{12}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{15}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sums 8,9,10,11,12 give 5+4+3+2+1 = 15 cells. \\frac{15}{36} = \\frac{5}{12}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum LESS than 8)?',
        options: ['\\frac{7}{12}', '\\frac{5}{12}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{5}{12} = \\frac{7}{12} (or count sums 2–7 = 21 cells).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(product = 12)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{4}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(2,6), (3,4), (4,3), (6,2) \\to 4 cells \\to \\frac{4}{36} = \\frac{1}{9}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(product = 1)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '0', '\\frac{1}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Only (1, 1) gives product 1.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(product is a square number) — squares from 1 to 36?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{9}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{8}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Square products: 1 (1,1); 4 (1,4),(4,1),(2,2); 9 (3,3); 16 (4,4); 25 (5,5); 36 (6,6). Total 8 cells \\to \\frac{8}{36} = \\frac{2}{9}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two dice rolled. P(sum is even)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{5}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Even-sum cells = 18 out of 36 = \\frac{1}{2}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L9: Independent events (multiplication) ───────
  {
    id: 'L9',
    title: 'Lesson 9 · Independent events (multiplication rule)',
    teach: {
      heading: 'P(A and B) = P(A) \\times P(B) — when A and B are independent',
      body: [
        'Two events are INDEPENDENT if the outcome of one has NO effect on the probability of the other. Tossing a coin and rolling a die are independent — knowing the coin landed heads tells you nothing about the die.',
        'For independent events: P(A AND B) = P(A) \\times P(B).',
        'This extends: P(A and B and C) = P(A) \\times P(B) \\times P(C) when all three are mutually independent.',
        'Common examples: tossing a coin twice (each toss independent), rolling a die multiple times, drawing a ball WITH REPLACEMENT (replacing the ball restores the bag).',
        'Without replacement, draws are NOT independent — we will look at that in a later chapter.',
      ],
      example: 'Coin tossed twice. P(two heads) = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{1}{4}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Coin tossed twice. P(two heads)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{2}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Coin tossed three times. P(three heads)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{8}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{3}{8}', '\\frac{1}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{1}{8}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Die rolled twice. P(two sixes)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{2}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{6} \\times \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{1}{36}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Bag of 12 balls (5 red, 4 white, 3 blue). Two drawn WITH REPLACEMENT. P(both red)?',
        options: ['\\frac{25}{144}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{5}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{5}{12} \\times \\frac{5}{12} = \\frac{25}{144}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same bag, with replacement. P(red, then white)?',
        options: ['\\frac{20}{144}', '\\frac{9}{144}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{1}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{5}{12} \\times \\frac{4}{12} = \\frac{20}{144} = \\frac{5}{36}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Simone shoots: P(score) = 0.1. Rami shoots: P(score) = 0.2. P(both score)?',
        options: ['0.02', '0.3', '0.12', '0.2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.1 \\times 0.2 = 0.02 (independent).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Simone (0.1) and Rami (0.2). P(Simone scores AND Rami misses)?',
        options: ['0.08', '0.1', '0.18', '0.02'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.1 \\times (1 \\u2013 0.2) = 0.1 \\times 0.8 = 0.08.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two cards drawn from a deck WITH REPLACEMENT. P(both kings)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{169}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{2}{52}', '\\frac{1}{52}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{13} \\times \\frac{1}{13} = \\frac{1}{169}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Coin tossed FOUR times. P(four heads)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{16}', '\\frac{1}{8}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{4}{16}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^4 = \\frac{1}{16}.' },
      { kind: 'fill-frac', prompt: 'A coin with P(H) = \\frac{1}{3} is tossed three times. P(three heads) as simplified fraction?', answer: '1/27',
        solution: '\\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\right)^3 = \\frac{1}{27}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L10: Mutually exclusive events ────────────────
  {
    id: 'L10',
    title: 'Lesson 10 · Mutually exclusive events (addition rule)',
    teach: {
      heading: 'P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) — when A and B cannot both happen',
      body: [
        'Two events are MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE if they CANNOT happen at the same time. E.g. on one die roll, "scoring 3" and "scoring 5" are mutually exclusive — you cannot get both.',
        'For mutually exclusive events: P(A OR B) = P(A) + P(B).',
        'Warning: this rule ONLY works if A and B are mutually exclusive. For events that COULD both happen (e.g. "even" and "less than 4" on a die — both happen for the outcome 2), use the more general rule P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) \\u2013 P(A and B).',
        'Many "complement" calculations use this idea: the events "A happens" and "A does not happen" are always mutually exclusive (one must happen, both cannot).',
      ],
      example: 'Roll a fair die. P(2 OR 5) = \\frac{1}{6} + \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{2}{6} = \\frac{1}{3}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Die rolled. P(rolling a 1 OR a 6)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{12}', '\\frac{1}{2}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{6} + \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{2}{6} = \\frac{1}{3} (mutually exclusive).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Die rolled. P(odd OR scoring exactly 6)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{5}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Odds = \\{1,3,5\\} = \\frac{3}{6}; 6 is none of those, so add: \\frac{3}{6} + \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{4}{6} = \\frac{2}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Bag with 12 balls: 5 red, 4 white, 3 blue. P(red OR blue)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{5}{12}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{8}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mutually exclusive: \\frac{5}{12} + \\frac{3}{12} = \\frac{8}{12} = \\frac{2}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Are "rolling an even number" and "rolling a 6" mutually exclusive on one die roll?',
        options: ['No — 6 is even, so they happen together', 'Yes', 'Cannot tell', 'Only on a fair die'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Both events occur for the outcome 6.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Are "rolling a 2" and "rolling a 5" mutually exclusive?',
        options: ['Yes', 'No', 'Only sometimes', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'A single roll cannot be both.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Die rolled. Use the formula P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) \\u2013 P(A and B). P(even OR multiple of 3)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{3}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{5}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Evens \\frac{3}{6}; mults of 3 \\frac{2}{6}; both = \\{6\\} = \\frac{1}{6}. Total = \\frac{3+2-1}{6} = \\frac{4}{6} = \\frac{2}{3}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Spinner sectors are red (P = 0.4), green (P = 0.3), blue (P = 0.2), yellow (P = 0.1). P(red OR yellow)?',
        options: ['0.5', '0.4', '0.6', '0.7'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.4 + 0.1 = 0.5 (mutually exclusive — one sector at a time).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same spinner. P(NOT red and NOT yellow)?',
        options: ['0.5', '0.3', '0.6', '0.2'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 0.5 = 0.5 (the complement).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Cards drawn from deck. P(king OR queen)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{13}', '\\frac{1}{13}', '\\frac{8}{52}', 'A and C'], correct: 3,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{52} + \\frac{4}{52} = \\frac{8}{52} = \\frac{2}{13} (mutually exclusive).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Card drawn from deck. P(heart OR queen) — be careful!',
        options: ['\\frac{4}{13}', '\\frac{17}{52}', '\\frac{2}{13}', '\\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{1}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'NOT mutually exclusive (queen of hearts is in both). \\frac{13 + 4 - 1}{52} = \\frac{16}{52} = \\frac{4}{13}.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L11: Combining: at least one, neither, only one
  {
    id: 'L11',
    title: 'Lesson 11 · At least one, neither, only one',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Decomposing combined events into independent pieces',
      body: [
        'When two independent events A and B can each happen or not, there are FOUR mutually exclusive outcomes: (A and B), (A and not B), (not A and B), (not A and not B).',
        'NEITHER happens: P(A\\u2032 and B\\u2032) = (1 \\u2013 P(A))(1 \\u2013 P(B)).',
        'AT LEAST ONE happens: 1 \\u2013 P(neither) = 1 \\u2013 (1 \\u2013 P(A))(1 \\u2013 P(B)).',
        'EXACTLY ONE happens (only A, or only B): P(A and B\\u2032) + P(A\\u2032 and B) = P(A)(1 \\u2013 P(B)) + (1 \\u2013 P(A))P(B).',
        'BOTH happen: P(A) \\times P(B) (the multiplication rule for independent events).',
      ],
      example: 'P(Noa passes) = \\frac{1}{3}, P(Sunja passes) = \\frac{5}{6}. P(both) = \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{5}{6} = \\frac{5}{18}. P(neither) = \\frac{2}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{2}{18} = \\frac{1}{9}. P(at least one) = 1 \\u2013 \\frac{1}{9} = \\frac{8}{9}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(A) = 0.2, P(B) = 0.3, independent. P(A and B)?',
        options: ['0.06', '0.5', '0.1', '0.06%'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.2 \\times 0.3 = 0.06.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(A) = 0.2, P(B) = 0.3, independent. P(neither)?',
        options: ['0.56', '0.5', '0.06', '0.94'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(1 \\u2013 0.2)(1 \\u2013 0.3) = 0.8 \\times 0.7 = 0.56.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(A) = 0.2, P(B) = 0.3, independent. P(at LEAST one)?',
        options: ['0.44', '0.5', '0.56', '0.06'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 0.56 = 0.44.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(A) = 0.2, P(B) = 0.3, independent. P(exactly one)?',
        options: ['0.38', '0.5', '0.44', '0.56'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.2 \\times 0.7 + 0.8 \\times 0.3 = 0.14 + 0.24 = 0.38.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'P(Noa passes) = \\frac{1}{3}, P(Sunja passes) = \\frac{5}{6}, independent. P(both pass)?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{18}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{18}', '\\frac{5}{6}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{5}{6} = \\frac{5}{18}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Noa & Sunja. P(neither passes)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{2}{18}', '\\frac{1}{18}', 'A and B'], correct: 3,
        solution: '\\frac{2}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{2}{18} = \\frac{1}{9}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Noa & Sunja. P(at least one passes)?',
        options: ['\\frac{8}{9}', '\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{5}{18}', '\\frac{17}{18}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 \\frac{1}{9} = \\frac{8}{9}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Noa & Sunja. P(only ONE of them passes)?',
        options: ['\\frac{11}{18}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{5}{18}', '\\frac{8}{9}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'P(N pass, S fail) + P(N fail, S pass) = \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{6} + \\frac{2}{3} \\times \\frac{5}{6} = \\frac{1}{18} + \\frac{10}{18} = \\frac{11}{18}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Simone (P = 0.1) and Rami (P = 0.2) shoot. P(at least one scores)?',
        options: ['0.28', '0.3', '0.02', '0.72'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 (0.9)(0.8) = 1 \\u2013 0.72 = 0.28.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Simone & Rami. P(EXACTLY one scores)?',
        options: ['0.26', '0.3', '0.28', '0.02'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.1 \\times 0.8 + 0.9 \\times 0.2 = 0.08 + 0.18 = 0.26.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L12: Word problems · single events ────────────
  {
    id: 'L12',
    title: 'Lesson 12 · Word problems · single events',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Translate the words into "favourable / total"',
      body: [
        'Real-world probability questions are usually descriptions of a sampling experiment. Your job is to (1) identify the SAMPLE SPACE — what are all the equally likely outcomes? — and (2) count the FAVOURABLE outcomes the question asks about.',
        'Common situations: a bag of identical objects with different labels, a numbered spinner, a deck of cards, a survey of N people, a quality-control check on a production batch.',
        'For SURVEY data: the experimental probability that a random person from the same population has property X is roughly \\frac{number who have X}{number surveyed}.',
        'For EXPECTED occurrences: in N future trials, expect about N \\times P successes — a useful sanity check on the size of the answer.',
      ],
      example: 'A bowl has 3 apples, 4 bananas, 2 pears, 1 orange (10 fruit). P(picking a banana) = \\frac{4}{10} = \\frac{2}{5}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bowl has 3 apples, 4 bananas, 2 pears, 1 orange. P(picking a banana)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{5}', '\\frac{4}{10}', '\\frac{1}{4}', 'A and B'], correct: 3,
        solution: '\\frac{4}{10} = \\frac{2}{5}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same bowl. P(pear OR banana)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{5}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{6}{10}', 'A and C'], correct: 3,
        solution: '\\frac{6}{10} = \\frac{3}{5}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same bowl. P(picking a mango)?',
        options: ['0', '\\frac{1}{10}', '1', '\\frac{1}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'No mangoes in the bowl.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 22 random regular shapes: 6 triangles, 5 quadrilaterals, 4 squares (also quadrilaterals), 3 pentagons, 4 hexagons. P(picking a triangle)?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{11}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{6}{16}', '\\frac{1}{2}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{6}{22} = \\frac{3}{11}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A 4-sided die has P(1) = \\frac{2}{9}, P(2) = \\frac{1}{3}, P(3) = \\frac{5}{18}. P(face 4)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{5}{18}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sum = 1: \\frac{4 + 6 + 5}{18} = \\frac{15}{18} \\to P(4) = \\frac{3}{18} = \\frac{1}{6}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag has 100 raffle tickets numbered 1–100. One drawn at random. P(number divisible by 5)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{5}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{10}', '\\frac{20}{100}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Multiples of 5 in 1–100: 20. \\frac{20}{100} = \\frac{1}{5}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Survey of 150 people. 60 prefer coffee. P(random person from this group prefers coffee)?',
        options: ['\\frac{2}{5}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{60}{90}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{60}{150} = \\frac{2}{5}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same coffee-survey (40% prefer coffee). In a town of 5000 people, expected number of coffee-drinkers?',
        options: ['2000', '1500', '500', '40%'], correct: 0,
        solution: '5000 \\times 0.4 = 2000.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag of 35 sweets contains 14 strawberry, 9 lemon, the rest mint. P(picking a mint sweet)?',
        options: ['\\frac{12}{35}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{14}{35}', '\\frac{9}{35}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mints = 35 \\u2013 14 \\u2013 9 = 12 \\to \\frac{12}{35}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A factory makes 20 000 units; 1.5% are defective. Expected number of defective units?',
        options: ['300', '150', '3000', '30'], correct: 0,
        solution: '20 000 \\times 0.015 = 300.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L13: Word problems · combined events ──────────
  {
    id: 'L13',
    title: 'Lesson 13 · Word problems · combined events',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Pick the right rule: \\times for "and", + for mutually-exclusive "or"',
      body: [
        'Real-world combined-event questions usually need two checks: (1) are the events INDEPENDENT? (use \\times) (2) are the events MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE? (use +).',
        '"And" with INDEPENDENT events: multiply. "Or" with MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE events: add. Otherwise apply the general rule: P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) \\u2013 P(A and B), or break the situation into the four (A, B), (A, B\\u2032), (A\\u2032, B), (A\\u2032, B\\u2032) cells.',
        '"At least one of A, B": often easier as 1 \\u2013 P(neither).',
        '"Exactly one of A, B": P(A and B\\u2032) + P(A\\u2032 and B). Always check by adding to the other three pieces — they should sum to 1.',
        'When the question describes a sequence of trials (e.g. "tossed three times"), use the multiplication rule once per trial.',
      ],
      example: 'Kirti and Hussein each take a driving test, independent. P(Kirti) = 0.7, P(Hussein) = 0.4. P(both) = 0.28, P(neither) = 0.18, P(only Kirti) = 0.42, P(at least one) = 0.82.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A coin tossed twice. P(heads BOTH times)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{3}{4}', '\\frac{2}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A coin with P(H) = \\frac{1}{3} is tossed three times. P(three heads in a row)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{27}', '\\frac{1}{9}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{3}{27}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\right)^3 = \\frac{1}{27}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two unbiased dice. P(sum is 11)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{18}', '\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{2}{36}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(5,6), (6,5) \\to \\frac{2}{36} = \\frac{1}{18}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two unbiased dice. P(sum is 6)?',
        options: ['\\frac{5}{36}', '\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{6}{36}', '\\frac{1}{12}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(1,5),(2,4),(3,3),(4,2),(5,1) \\to 5 cells.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two unbiased dice. P(BOTH show the same number)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{6}', '\\frac{1}{36}', '\\frac{6}{12}', '\\frac{1}{2}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '6 doubles in 36 cells.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Devin and Tej play cards (with replacement). P(Devin draws a queen AND Tej draws a queen)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{169}', '\\frac{1}{52}', '\\frac{4}{52}', '\\frac{1}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{13} \\times \\frac{1}{13} = \\frac{1}{169}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Devin draws a card from a deck (with replacement) and Tej draws another. P(both cards are red)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{169}', '\\frac{1}{13}'], correct: 0,
        solution: '\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{1}{4}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Devin & Tej. P(both cards are the SAME COLOUR)?',
        options: ['\\frac{1}{2}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{169}', '\\frac{2}{4}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Both red OR both black: \\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{1}{4} = \\frac{1}{2} (mutually exclusive).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Kirti and Hussein independent driving tests. P(Kirti) = 0.7, P(Hussein) = 0.4. P(both pass)?',
        options: ['0.28', '0.4', '0.7', '1.1'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.7 \\times 0.4 = 0.28.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Kirti & Hussein. P(at LEAST one passes)?',
        options: ['0.82', '0.28', '0.18', '0.7'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1 \\u2013 (1 \\u2013 0.7)(1 \\u2013 0.4) = 1 \\u2013 0.18 = 0.82.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same Kirti & Hussein. P(only Kirti passes)?',
        options: ['0.42', '0.28', '0.7', '0.12'], correct: 0,
        solution: '0.7 \\times 0.6 = 0.42.' },
    ],
  },
]

const CH8_PROGRESS_KEY = 'tenali-chapter8-progress'
function ch8_loadProgress() {
  try { return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(CH8_PROGRESS_KEY) || '{}') || {} } catch { return {} }
}
function ch8_saveProgress(p) { try { localStorage.setItem(CH8_PROGRESS_KEY, JSON.stringify(p)) } catch {} }

// --- Custom math renderer for Chapter 8 ----------------------------------
function Ch8Frac({ num, den }) {
  return (
    <span style={{
      display: 'inline-flex', flexDirection: 'column', alignItems: 'center',
      verticalAlign: 'middle', margin: '0 0.18em', lineHeight: 1.05,
      fontSize: '0.95em',
    }}>
      <span style={{ padding: '0 0.4em 0.05em', borderBottom: '1.6px solid currentColor' }}>{num}</span>
      <span style={{ padding: '0.05em 0.4em 0' }}>{den}</span>
    </span>
  )
}
function ch8_subOps(s) {
  return String(s)
    .replace(/\\times/g, '×').replace(/\\div/g, '÷')
    .replace(/\\approx/g, '≈').replace(/\\to\b/g, '→')
    .replace(/\\le\b/g, '≤').replace(/\\ge\b/g, '≥')
    .replace(/\\cdot/g, '·').replace(/\\pm/g, '±')
    .replace(/\\pi/g, 'π').replace(/\\theta/g, 'θ')
    .replace(/\\sqrt\{([^{}]+)\}/g, '√($1)')
    .replace(/\\sqrt(\d+)/g, '√$1')
    .replace(/\\ell\b/g, 'ℓ')
    .replace(/\\circ/g, '°')
    .replace(/\\u2113/g, 'ℓ')
    .replace(/\\u00b0/g, '°')
    .replace(/\\u2019/g, '’')
    .replace(/\\u2032/g, '′')
    .replace(/\\u2013/g, '–')
    .replace(/\\u2660/g, '♠')
    .replace(/\\u2663/g, '♣')
    .replace(/\\u2665/g, '♥')
    .replace(/\\u2666/g, '♦')
    .replace(/\\\$/g, '$').replace(/\\%/g, '%')
}
function ch8RenderMath(text) {
  if (text == null) return null
  const src = ch8_subOps(text)
  const out = []
  let i = 0, buf = ''
  const flush = () => { if (buf) { out.push(buf); buf = '' } }
  // Helper for \left( and \right) — render just as parentheses
  const cleanedSrc = src.replace(/\\left\(/g, '(').replace(/\\right\)/g, ')')
  const finalSrc = cleanedSrc
  while (i < finalSrc.length) {
    if (finalSrc.startsWith('\\frac{', i)) {
      flush()
      let j = i + 6, depth = 1
      const ns = j
      while (j < finalSrc.length) { if (finalSrc[j] === '{') depth++; else if (finalSrc[j] === '}') { depth--; if (depth === 0) break } j++ }
      const numStr = finalSrc.slice(ns, j); j++
      if (finalSrc[j] !== '{') { buf += finalSrc.slice(i, j); i = j; continue }
      j++; depth = 1
      const ds = j
      while (j < finalSrc.length) { if (finalSrc[j] === '{') depth++; else if (finalSrc[j] === '}') { depth--; if (depth === 0) break } j++ }
      const denStr = finalSrc.slice(ds, j); j++
      out.push(<Ch8Frac key={`f${out.length}`} num={ch8RenderMath(numStr)} den={ch8RenderMath(denStr)} />)
      i = j
    } else if (finalSrc[i] === '^') {
      const m = finalSrc.slice(i).match(/^\^(-?\d+)/)
      if (m) { flush(); out.push(<sup key={`s${out.length}`} style={{ fontSize: '0.72em', verticalAlign: 'super' }}>{m[1]}</sup>); i += m[0].length }
      else { buf += finalSrc[i]; i++ }
    } else { buf += finalSrc[i]; i++ }
  }
  flush()
  return out
}

const CH8_AUTO_ADVANCE_MS = 5000
// CH8_RETRY_GAP removed: wrong answers now appended to end of playList (see SKILL.md rule #5)

function Chapter8App({ onBack }) {
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState(ch8_loadProgress)
  const [activeId, setActiveId] = useState(null)
  const [phase, setPhase] = useState('teach')
  const [qIdx, setQIdx] = useState(0)
  const [playList, setPlayList] = useState([])
  const [lastWrongSrc, setLastWrongSrc] = useState(null)
  const [selectedIdx, setSelectedIdx] = useState(null)
  const [fillInput, setFillInput] = useState('')
  const [revealed, setRevealed] = useState(false)
  const [isCorrect, setIsCorrect] = useState(false)
  const [autoCountdown, setAutoCountdown] = useState(0)
  const inputRef = useRef(null)
  const autoTimerRef = useRef(null)
  const advanceRef = useRef(() => {})

  const lesson = activeId ? CH8_LESSONS.find(l => l.id === activeId) : null
  const currentSourceIdx = playList[qIdx]
  const currentQ = lesson && currentSourceIdx != null ? lesson.questions[currentSourceIdx] : null
  const isRetry = useMemo(() => {
    if (currentSourceIdx == null) return false
    return playList.slice(0, qIdx).includes(currentSourceIdx)
  }, [playList, qIdx, currentSourceIdx])

  const optionOrder = useMemo(() => {
    if (!currentQ || currentQ.kind !== 'mcq') return []
    return ch8_seededShuffle(currentQ.options.length, `${activeId}-${qIdx}-${currentSourceIdx}-${currentQ.prompt}`)
  }, [activeId, qIdx, currentSourceIdx, currentQ])
  const correctDisplayIdx = useMemo(() => optionOrder.indexOf(currentQ?.correct ?? -1), [optionOrder, currentQ])

  useEffect(() => { ch8_saveProgress(progress) }, [progress])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || revealed) return
    if (currentQ?.kind?.startsWith('fill') && inputRef.current) inputRef.current.focus()
  }, [phase, qIdx, revealed, currentQ])

  const startLesson = (id) => {
    setActiveId(id)
    const lessonRef = CH8_LESSONS.find(l => l.id === id)
    const initial = Array.from({ length: lessonRef.questions.length }, (_, i) => i)
    setPlayList(initial)
    setLastWrongSrc(null)
    const p = progress[id] || {}
    if (p.teachSeen) { setPhase('practice'); setQIdx(p.qIdx || 0) }
    else { setPhase('teach'); setQIdx(0) }
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
  }

  const acknowledgeTeach = () => {
    setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: 0 } }))
    setPhase('practice'); setQIdx(0)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
    setLastWrongSrc(null)
  }

  const submitFill = () => {
    if (!currentQ) return
    if (revealed) { advance(); return }
    const ok = ch8_checkFill(currentQ, fillInput)
    setIsCorrect(ok); setRevealed(true)
    setLastWrongSrc(ok ? null : currentSourceIdx)
  }

  const pickMcq = (displayIdx) => {
    if (!currentQ || revealed || currentQ.kind !== 'mcq') return
    const optSourceIdx = optionOrder[displayIdx]
    const ok = optSourceIdx === currentQ.correct
    setSelectedIdx(displayIdx); setIsCorrect(ok); setRevealed(true)
    setLastWrongSrc(ok ? null : currentSourceIdx)
  }

  const cancelAutoAdvance = () => {
    if (autoTimerRef.current) { clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null }
    setAutoCountdown(0)
  }

  const advance = () => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    if (!lesson) return
    let workingList = playList
    if (lastWrongSrc != null) {
      // Wrong answers go to the END of the lesson — student finishes all
      // fresh questions first, then meets the retry cluster at the tail.
      workingList = [...playList, lastWrongSrc]
      setPlayList(workingList)
      setLastWrongSrc(null)
    }
    const next = qIdx + 1
    if (next >= workingList.length) {
      setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: lesson.questions.length, completed: true } }))
      setPhase('done')
    } else {
      setQIdx(next)
      setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
      setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: Math.min(lesson.questions.length, next) } }))
    }
  }
  advanceRef.current = advance

  const jumpToQuestion = (i) => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    if (!lesson) return
    const clamped = Math.max(0, Math.min(playList.length - 1, i))
    setQIdx(clamped); setLastWrongSrc(null)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
    setProgress(p => {
      const cur = p[activeId] || {}
      const saved = Math.max(cur.qIdx || 0, Math.min(lesson.questions.length, clamped))
      return { ...p, [activeId]: { ...cur, teachSeen: true, qIdx: saved } }
    })
  }

  const backToOverview = () => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    setActiveId(null); setPhase('teach'); setQIdx(0)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
  }

  const resetAll = () => {
    if (!confirm('Reset all Chapter 8 progress?')) return
    setProgress({}); ch8_saveProgress({})
    backToOverview()
  }

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || !revealed) { cancelAutoAdvance(); return }
    const total = Math.round(CH8_AUTO_ADVANCE_MS / 1000)
    setAutoCountdown(total)
    autoTimerRef.current = setInterval(() => {
      setAutoCountdown(prev => {
        if (prev <= 1) {
          clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null
          advanceRef.current()
          return 0
        }
        return prev - 1
      })
    }, 1000)
    return () => { if (autoTimerRef.current) { clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null } }
  }, [phase, revealed, qIdx, activeId])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || !currentQ) return
    const onKey = (e) => {
      if (revealed) {
        if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') { e.preventDefault(); advance() }
        return
      }
      if (currentQ.kind === 'mcq') {
        const k = e.key
        if (/^[1-9]$/.test(k)) {
          const i = parseInt(k, 10) - 1
          if (i < currentQ.options.length) { e.preventDefault(); pickMcq(i) }
        }
      } else if (currentQ.kind?.startsWith('fill')) {
        if (e.key === 'Enter') { e.preventDefault(); submitFill() }
      }
    }
    window.addEventListener('keydown', onKey)
    return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', onKey)
  }, [phase, qIdx, revealed, currentQ, fillInput, optionOrder])

  // ────────── Overview ──────────
  if (!activeId) {
    const total = CH8_LESSONS.length
    const done = CH8_LESSONS.filter(l => progress[l.id]?.completed).length
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 760, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, alignItems: 'center', marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={onBack}>← Home</button>
          <button className="back-button" style={{ marginLeft: 'auto' }} onClick={resetAll}>Reset progress</button>
        </div>
        <h1 style={{ marginBottom: 4 }}>Chapter 8 — Introduction to Probability</h1>
        <p className="subtitle" style={{ marginTop: 0 }}>
          Cambridge IGCSE Mathematics · {done}/{total} lessons complete
        </p>
        <p style={{ opacity: 0.85, marginTop: 8 }}>
          Pick the next lesson. Each one starts with a short explanation, then a stream of multiple-choice and fill-in-the-blank
          questions — easy warm-ups first, then the actual chapter exercise problems.
        </p>
        <ol style={{ listStyle: 'none', padding: 0, marginTop: 16 }}>
          {CH8_LESSONS.map((l) => {
            const p = progress[l.id] || {}
            const completed = p.completed
            const inProg = !completed && (p.teachSeen || (p.qIdx || 0) > 0)
            return (
              <li key={l.id} style={{ marginBottom: 8 }}>
                <button
                  onClick={() => startLesson(l.id)}
                  style={{
                    width: '100%', textAlign: 'left', padding: '12px 14px',
                    borderRadius: 10,
                    borderLeft: completed ? '4px solid #2ea043' : inProg ? '4px solid #388bfd' : '1px solid var(--clr-border, #444)',
                    borderTop: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    borderRight: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    borderBottom: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    background: completed
                      ? 'linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(46,160,67,0.32) 0%, rgba(46,160,67,0.18) 100%)'
                      : inProg ? 'rgba(56,139,253,0.10)' : 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
                    color: 'var(--clr-text)',
                    fontWeight: completed ? 600 : 400,
                    cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem',
                    boxShadow: completed ? '0 0 0 1px rgba(46,160,67,0.35) inset' : 'none',
                  }}
                >
                  <span style={{ marginRight: 8 }}>{completed ? '✅' : inProg ? '▶' : '○'}</span>
                  {ch8RenderMath(l.title)}
                  {completed && (
                    <span style={{
                      float: 'right', fontSize: '0.72rem', fontWeight: 700, letterSpacing: '0.5px',
                      color: '#fff', background: '#2ea043', padding: '2px 8px', borderRadius: 10,
                    }}>DONE</span>
                  )}
                  {p.qIdx > 0 && !completed && (
                    <span style={{ float: 'right', fontSize: '0.8rem', opacity: 0.7 }}>{p.qIdx}/{l.questions.length}</span>
                  )}
                </button>
              </li>
            )
          })}
        </ol>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Teach ──────────
  if (phase === 'teach') {
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        </div>
        <h2 style={{ marginBottom: 4 }}>{ch8RenderMath(lesson.title)}</h2>
        <h3 style={{ color: 'var(--clr-accent, #6cf)', marginTop: 16 }}>{ch8RenderMath(lesson.teach.heading)}</h3>
        {lesson.teach.body.map((para, i) => (
          <p key={i} style={{ lineHeight: 1.7, marginBottom: 10, fontSize: '1rem' }}>{ch8RenderMath(para)}</p>
        ))}
        <div style={{
          marginTop: 14, padding: 14, borderRadius: 8,
          background: 'rgba(108,206,255,0.08)', border: '1px solid rgba(108,206,255,0.25)',
          fontSize: '1rem', lineHeight: 1.7,
        }}>
          <strong>Worked example: </strong>{ch8RenderMath(lesson.teach.example)}
        </div>
        {lesson.qFormat && <p style={{ marginTop: 14, fontSize: '0.9rem', opacity: 0.8 }}><em>Note:</em> {lesson.qFormat}</p>}
        <button onClick={acknowledgeTeach} style={{
          marginTop: 18, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8, fontSize: '1rem',
          background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)', color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer',
        }}>I've got it — start questions →</button>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Done ──────────
  if (phase === 'done') {
    const idx = CH8_LESSONS.findIndex(l => l.id === activeId)
    const next = CH8_LESSONS[idx + 1]
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        </div>
        <h2>🎉 Lesson complete</h2>
        <p>You finished <strong>{ch8RenderMath(lesson.title)}</strong>.</p>
        {next ? (
          <button onClick={() => startLesson(next.id)} style={{
            marginTop: 12, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8, fontSize: '1rem',
            background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)', color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer',
          }}>Next: {ch8RenderMath(next.title)} →</button>
        ) : (
          <p style={{ marginTop: 16, fontSize: '1.05rem' }}>🎓 You've completed every lesson in Chapter 8.</p>
        )}
        <button onClick={backToOverview} style={{
          marginTop: 12, marginLeft: 8, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8,
          background: 'transparent', color: 'var(--clr-text)', border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', cursor: 'pointer',
        }}>Back to lessons</button>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Practice ──────────
  const sliderMax = Math.max(1, playList.length)
  return (
    <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
      <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 12, alignItems: 'center' }}>
        <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        <button className="back-button" onClick={() => setPhase('teach')}>📖 Re-read teach</button>
        <span style={{ marginLeft: 'auto', fontSize: '0.85rem', opacity: 0.75 }}>
          Question {qIdx + 1} / {sliderMax}
          {sliderMax > lesson.questions.length && (
            <span style={{ marginLeft: 6, color: '#f0a020' }}>· {sliderMax - lesson.questions.length} retry queued</span>
          )}
        </span>
      </div>
      <h3 style={{ marginBottom: 8 }}>{ch8RenderMath(lesson.title)}</h3>
      <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 12, marginBottom: 18 }}>
        <span style={{ fontSize: '0.78rem', opacity: 0.65, minWidth: 18, textAlign: 'right' }}>1</span>
        <input
          type="range"
          min={1}
          max={sliderMax}
          value={qIdx + 1}
          onChange={e => jumpToQuestion(parseInt(e.target.value, 10) - 1)}
          aria-label="Jump to question"
          style={{
            flex: 1, accentColor: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
            cursor: 'pointer', height: 22,
          }}
        />
        <span style={{ fontSize: '0.78rem', opacity: 0.65, minWidth: 22 }}>{sliderMax}</span>
      </div>

      <div style={{
        padding: '22px 24px', borderRadius: 10, background: 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
        border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #333)', marginBottom: 16,
        fontSize: '1.25rem', lineHeight: 2.1, textAlign: 'center',
        display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center', minHeight: 80,
        position: 'relative',
      }}>
        {isRetry && (
          <span style={{
            position: 'absolute', top: 8, right: 12, fontSize: '0.7rem', fontWeight: 700,
            letterSpacing: '0.5px', color: '#f0a020', background: 'rgba(240,160,32,0.15)',
            border: '1px solid rgba(240,160,32,0.45)', padding: '2px 8px', borderRadius: 10,
          }}>↻ RETRY</span>
        )}
        <span>{ch8RenderMath(currentQ.prompt)}</span>
      </div>

      {currentQ.kind === 'mcq' ? (
        <div className="options-list">
          {optionOrder.map((srcIdx, displayIdx) => {
            const opt = currentQ.options[srcIdx]
            const isSelected = selectedIdx === displayIdx
            const isCorrectOpt = revealed && correctDisplayIdx === displayIdx
            const isWrongPick = revealed && isSelected && !isCorrect
            return (
              <button
                key={displayIdx}
                className={`option-card ${isSelected ? 'selected' : ''} ${isCorrectOpt ? 'correct-option' : ''} ${isWrongPick ? 'wrong-option' : ''}`}
                onClick={() => pickMcq(displayIdx)}
                disabled={revealed}
                style={{
                  borderColor: isCorrectOpt ? 'var(--clr-correct, #2ea043)' : isWrongPick ? 'var(--clr-wrong, #f85149)' : undefined,
                  background: isCorrectOpt ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.15)' : isWrongPick ? 'rgba(248,81,73,0.15)' : undefined,
                  display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center',
                  position: 'relative', padding: '18px 24px', minHeight: 64,
                  fontSize: '1.1rem', lineHeight: 1.9,
                }}
              >
                <span style={{
                  position: 'absolute', left: 18, top: '50%', transform: 'translateY(-50%)',
                  fontWeight: 700, opacity: 0.6, fontSize: '0.95rem',
                }}>{CH8_OPTION_LABEL[displayIdx]}.</span>
                <span style={{ display: 'inline-flex', alignItems: 'center' }}>{ch8RenderMath(opt)}</span>
              </button>
            )
          })}
        </div>
      ) : (
        <>
          <input
            ref={inputRef}
            type="text"
            value={fillInput}
            onChange={e => setFillInput(e.target.value)}
            disabled={revealed}
            placeholder="Your answer…"
            autoComplete="off"
            style={{
              width: '100%', padding: '14px 16px', fontSize: '1.15rem', borderRadius: 8,
              border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', textAlign: 'center',
              background: revealed ? 'rgba(255,255,255,0.04)' : 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
              color: 'var(--clr-text)', boxSizing: 'border-box',
            }}
          />
          {!revealed && (
            <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginTop: 12, justifyContent: 'center' }}>
              <button onClick={submitFill} disabled={!fillInput.trim()} style={{
                padding: '10px 22px', borderRadius: 6, background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
                color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem',
                opacity: fillInput.trim() ? 1 : 0.5,
              }}>Check</button>
            </div>
          )}
        </>
      )}

      {revealed && (
        <>
          <div style={{
            marginTop: 16, padding: 16, borderRadius: 8,
            background: isCorrect ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.15)' : 'rgba(248,81,73,0.15)',
            border: `1px solid ${isCorrect ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.45)' : 'rgba(248,81,73,0.45)'}`,
            fontSize: '1rem', lineHeight: 1.9,
          }}>
            <strong>{isCorrect ? '✅ Correct!' : '❌ Not quite.'}</strong>
            <div style={{ marginTop: 8, display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: 6 }}>
              <strong>Answer:</strong>
              <span>{currentQ.kind === 'mcq'
                ? ch8RenderMath(currentQ.options[currentQ.correct])
                : ch8RenderMath(String(currentQ.answer))}</span>
            </div>
            {currentQ.solution && (
              <div style={{ marginTop: 8, opacity: 0.9, display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: 6 }}>
                <strong>Working:</strong>
                <span>{ch8RenderMath(currentQ.solution)}</span>
              </div>
            )}
          </div>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 12, marginTop: 14, justifyContent: 'center' }}>
            <button onClick={advance} style={{
              padding: '12px 28px', borderRadius: 8, background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
              color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '1rem', fontWeight: 600,
            }}>
              {qIdx + 1 === lesson.questions.length ? 'Finish lesson →' : 'Next →'}
            </button>
            <span style={{ fontSize: '0.85rem', opacity: 0.65 }}>
              auto-advance in {autoCountdown}s · or press <kbd style={{ padding: '1px 6px', border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', borderRadius: 4, fontSize: '0.78rem' }}>Enter</kbd>
            </span>
          </div>
        </>
      )}
    </div>
  )
}

/* =====================================================================
 *  Chapter9App — Cambridge IGCSE Chapter 9 (Sequences, Surds and Sets)
 *
 *  Mounted at /chapter9. Same UX as Chapter5App–Chapter8App: ordered
 *  chain of lessons, every one unlocked from the start, slider to jump
 *  questions, MCQ with 1-9 keys + fill-in fallbacks, 5s auto-advance,
 *  completed lessons go green (with readable text), wrong answers
 *  appended to END of playList. See Tenali/skills/igcse-chapter/SKILL.md
 *  for the full pattern.
 * ===================================================================== */

const CH9_OPTION_LABEL = ['1','2','3','4','5','6','7','8','9']

function ch9_seededShuffle(n, key) {
  let h = 2166136261
  for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) { h ^= key.charCodeAt(i); h = Math.imul(h, 16777619) }
  const rand = () => { h = Math.imul(h ^ (h >>> 15), 2246822507); h = Math.imul(h ^ (h >>> 13), 3266489909); return ((h ^= h >>> 16) >>> 0) / 4294967295 }
  const arr = Array.from({ length: n }, (_, i) => i)
  for (let i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) { const j = Math.floor(rand() * (i + 1)); [arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]] }
  return arr
}

function ch9_gcd(a, b) { a = Math.abs(a); b = Math.abs(b); while (b) { [a, b] = [b, a % b] } return a || 1 }
function ch9_reduce(n, d) {
  if (d === 0) return null
  if (d < 0) { n = -n; d = -d }
  const g = ch9_gcd(n, d)
  return { n: n / g, d: d / g }
}
function ch9_parseFrac(raw) {
  if (raw == null) return null
  let s = String(raw).trim().replace(/\\frac\{(-?\d+)\}\{(-?\d+)\}/g, '$1/$2').replace(/\s+/g, ' ').replace(/–/g, '-')
  if (!s) return null
  const mixed = s.match(/^(-?)(\d+)\s+(\d+)\s*\/\s*(\d+)$/)
  if (mixed) {
    const sign = mixed[1] === '-' ? -1 : 1
    const w = +mixed[2], n = +mixed[3], d = +mixed[4]
    if (d === 0) return null
    return ch9_reduce(sign * (w * d + n), d)
  }
  const frac = s.match(/^(-?\d+)\s*\/\s*(-?\d+)$/)
  if (frac) {
    const n = +frac[1], d = +frac[2]
    if (d === 0) return null
    return ch9_reduce(n, d)
  }
  const num = Number(s)
  if (Number.isFinite(num)) {
    if (Number.isInteger(num)) return { n: num, d: 1 }
    const sign = num < 0 ? -1 : 1
    const decimals = (s.split('.')[1] || '').length
    const denom = Math.pow(10, decimals)
    return ch9_reduce(sign * Math.round(Math.abs(num) * denom), denom)
  }
  return null
}
function ch9_fracEqual(a, b) { return a && b && a.n === b.n && a.d === b.d }
function ch9_normalizeNumStr(s) {
  return String(s).trim().replace(/[$,\s%]/g, '').replace(/–/g, '-')
}
function ch9_numEqual(user, expected, tol) {
  const u = parseFloat(ch9_normalizeNumStr(user))
  if (!Number.isFinite(u)) return false
  const t = tol != null ? tol : Math.max(0.005, Math.abs(expected) * 0.005)
  return Math.abs(u - expected) <= t
}

function ch9_checkFill(q, raw) {
  if (!raw || !raw.trim()) return false
  switch (q.kind) {
    case 'fill-num': return ch9_numEqual(raw, q.answer, q.tol)
    case 'fill-frac': {
      const u = ch9_parseFrac(raw)
      const e = ch9_parseFrac(q.answer)
      return ch9_fracEqual(u, e)
    }
    case 'fill-text': return raw.trim().toLowerCase() === String(q.answer).trim().toLowerCase()
    default: return false
  }
}

// --- Lesson catalogue ---------------------------------------------------
// Cambridge IGCSE Chapter 9 — Sequences, Surds and Sets
// Sections covered: 9.1 Sequences (term-to-term rules, linear/quadratic
// nth terms, special sequences, subscript notation); 9.2 Rational and
// irrational numbers (inc. recurring decimals → fractions); 9.3 Surds
// (simplify, +/-, ×/÷, rationalise); 9.4 Sets (notation, ∪/∩/⊂, Venn,
// set builder). See uploads PDF p. 265-311.
const CH9_LESSONS = [
  // ───────────────────── L1: Term-to-term rules ────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L1',
    title: 'Lesson 1 · Term-to-term rules',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Spot the rule that takes one term to the next',
      body: [
        'A SEQUENCE is an ordered list of numbers (or shapes) called TERMS, formed by some rule. The rule that says how to get from one term to the next is the TERM-TO-TERM rule.',
        'Common term-to-term rules: ADD a constant (e.g. 2, 5, 8, 11, … add 3), SUBTRACT a constant (e.g. 30, 25, 20, … subtract 5), MULTIPLY by a constant (e.g. 2, 6, 18, 54, … times 3), DIVIDE by a constant.',
        'Some sequences combine rules — Fibonacci adds the previous TWO terms (1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, …).',
        'To CONTINUE a sequence: spot the rule, then apply it to the last term you know.',
      ],
      example: 'Sequence: 2, 4, 8, 16, … rule is "multiply by 2"; next term is 16 \\times 2 = 32.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 5, 8, 11, 14, …?',
        options: ['17', '18', '19', '15'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Add 3: 14 + 3 = 17.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, …?',
        options: ['32', '24', '20', '64'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Multiply by 2: 16 \\times 2 = 32.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 50, 45, 40, 35, …?',
        options: ['30', '25', '40', '32'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Subtract 5: 35 - 5 = 30.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 3, 9, 27, 81, …?',
        options: ['243', '162', '108', '324'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Multiply by 3: 81 \\times 3 = 243.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, …? (Fibonacci)',
        options: ['13', '11', '16', '12'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Add the two previous: 5 + 8 = 13.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Term-to-term rule for 1, 4, 16, 64, …?',
        options: ['Multiply by 4', 'Add 3 then 12 then 48', 'Multiply by 3', 'Square the previous'], correct: 0,
        solution: '64 / 16 = 4 and 16 / 4 = 4 and 4 / 1 = 4.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 100, 50, 25, 12.5, …?',
        options: ['6.25', '0', '6', '5'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Divide by 2: 12.5 / 2 = 6.25.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Next term in 7, 11, 15, 19, …?', answer: 23,
        solution: 'Add 4.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Next term in 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, …?',
        options: ['36', '30', '49', '32'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'These are square numbers 1², 2², 3², 4², 5²; next is 6² = 36.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Next term in 2, 6, 18, 54, …?', answer: 162,
        solution: 'Multiply by 3.' },
    ],
