  // ───────────────────── L8: Perpendicular lines ───────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L8',
    title: 'Lesson 8 · Perpendicular lines',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Gradients multiply to -1',
      body: [
        'Two lines (neither vertical nor horizontal) are PERPENDICULAR if and only if the product of their gradients is -1: m_1 \\times m_2 = -1.',
        'Equivalently, the gradient of a perpendicular line is the NEGATIVE RECIPROCAL of the original.',
        'Negative reciprocal of 2 is -\\frac{1}{2}; of -\\frac{3}{4} is \\frac{4}{3}; of -1 is 1.',
        'Special cases: a vertical line (x = a) is perpendicular to any horizontal line (y = b).',
        'To write the perpendicular line through a given point: take the negative reciprocal of the gradient, then use the point to find c.',
      ],
      example: 'y = 2x + 3 has gradient 2. The perpendicular has gradient -\\frac{1}{2}.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Negative reciprocal of 4?',
        options: ['-\\frac{1}{4}', '\\frac{1}{4}', '-4', '4'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Flip and negate.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Negative reciprocal of -\\frac{2}{3}?',
        options: ['\\frac{3}{2}', '-\\frac{3}{2}', '\\frac{2}{3}', '-\\frac{2}{3}'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Flip to -\\frac{3}{2}, negate to \\frac{3}{2}.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A line has gradient 3. Gradient of any perpendicular line?',
        options: ['-\\frac{1}{3}', '\\frac{1}{3}', '-3', '3'], correct: 0,
