  // ───────────────────── L11: Volumes of similar solids ─────────────────
  {
    id: 'L11',
    title: 'Lesson 11 · Volumes of similar solids',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Volume_2 = Volume_1 \\times k^3',
      body: [
        'Two similar solids have a single linear scale factor k. Volume scales by k^3.',
        '\\frac{V_2}{V_1} = \\left(\\frac{length_2}{length_1}\\right)^3 = k^3.',
        'In reverse: linear scale factor = \\sqrt[3]{volume ratio}.',
        'Useful in real life: doubling all dimensions of a box gives 8× the volume; the cost of paint scales with surface area (k^2), but the cost of filling scales with volume (k^3).',
      ],
      example: 'A small cone has volume 16 cm^3. A similar cone has linear scale factor 3. Larger volume = 16 × 27 = 432 cm^3.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Linear scale factor 2. Volume ratio (small : big)?',
        options: ['1 : 8', '1 : 2', '1 : 4', '1 : 6'], correct: 0,
        solution: '1^3 : 2^3.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Linear scale factor 5. Volume scale factor?',
        options: ['125', '25', '5', '15'], correct: 0,
        solution: '5^3.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two similar cylinders. Radii 2 and 6. Volume ratio?',
        options: ['1 : 27', '1 : 3', '1 : 9', '1 : 18'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(2/6)^3 = 1/27.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A shipping crate doubles in every dimension. Volume increases by factor …',
        options: ['8', '4', '2', '6'], correct: 0,
