    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L13: Congruent triangles (SSS, SAS, ASA, RHS) ──
  {
    id: 'L13',
    title: 'Lesson 13 · Congruent triangles',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Same shape AND same size',
      body: [
        'Two shapes are CONGRUENT if they are the SAME shape AND the SAME size — one can be slid, rotated, or flipped onto the other.',
        'For triangles, FOUR criteria each suffice to prove congruence:',
        'SSS: three corresponding sides equal.',
        'SAS: two corresponding sides equal AND the angle BETWEEN them equal.',
        'ASA: two corresponding angles equal AND the side BETWEEN them equal.',
        'RHS: in right-angled triangles, the right angle, the hypotenuse, and one other side equal.',
        'Note that SSA (two sides and a non-included angle) is NOT a valid criterion in general.',
      ],
      example: '\\triangle ABC has sides 3, 4, 5. \\triangle DEF has sides 3, 4, 5. By SSS they are congruent.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Which is NOT a congruence criterion?',
        options: ['SSA', 'SSS', 'SAS', 'ASA'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'SSA is ambiguous in general.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two triangles with sides 5, 6, 7 and 5, 6, 7 — congruent?',
        options: ['Yes (SSS)', 'No', 'Only similar', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'All three pairs equal.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two triangles with two sides and the included angle equal — congruent?',
        options: ['Yes (SAS)', 'No', 'Only similar', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'SAS criterion.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Right triangles with hypotenuse 13 and one leg 5; another with hypotenuse 13 and one leg 5 — congruent?',
        options: ['Yes (RHS)', 'No', 'Only similar', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'RHS.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Are CONGRUENT shapes similar?',
        options: ['Yes (with k = 1)', 'No', 'Only sometimes', 'Only if equilateral'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Congruent = similar with scale 1.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Are SIMILAR shapes always congruent?',
        options: ['No (sizes can differ)', 'Yes', 'Only triangles', 'Only if angles equal'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Similar allows any positive scale factor.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two triangles with angles 30°/60°/90° and same hypotenuse. Congruent?',
        options: ['Yes (RHS or AAS)', 'No', 'Only similar', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'AAS or RHS — sides are determined.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two triangles with all three angles equal — congruent?',
        options: ['Not necessarily — only similar', 'Yes', 'Only if right-angled', 'Only equilateral'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'AAA implies similarity, not congruence.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'For congruent triangles ABC ≡ DEF, AB corresponds to …',
        options: ['DE', 'EF', 'DF', 'BC'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Vertex order: A↔D, B↔E.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two equilateral triangles of side 6 — congruent?',
        options: ['Yes (SSS)', 'No', 'Only similar', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Same shape and size.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L14: Working with congruent shapes ─────────────
  {
    id: 'L14',
    title: 'Lesson 14 · Working with congruent shapes',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Use congruence to copy facts between figures',
      body: [
        'Once two shapes are known to be CONGRUENT, every corresponding length and angle is equal.',
        'Use the corresponding-vertex order to figure out which side or angle in one shape matches which in the other.',
        'A common task: split a figure into congruent pieces (e.g. a rectangle by its diagonal into two congruent triangles).',
        'Another: prove a quadrilateral is a kite/rhombus/parallelogram by showing two pairs of congruent triangles.',
      ],
      example: 'A rectangle ABCD with diagonal BD splits into \\triangle ABD and \\triangle CDB which are CONGRUENT (SSS or SAS), so AB = CD, AD = BC, and the diagonal equals itself.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Diagonal of a rectangle splits it into …',
        options: ['Two congruent triangles', 'Two similar but unequal triangles', 'Three triangles', 'Four squares'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'SSS or SAS gives congruence.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Diagonal of a parallelogram (not rectangle) splits it into …',
        options: ['Two congruent triangles', 'Two unequal triangles', 'Two right triangles', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'SAS or SSS via opposite-side equality.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A square has 2 diagonals. They split the square into how many CONGRUENT triangles?',
        options: ['4', '2', '8', '1'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Both diagonals together: 4 congruent right isosceles triangles.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In a kite ABCD (AB = AD and CB = CD), which triangles are congruent?',
        options: ['ABC and ADC', 'ABD and BCD', 'ABD and ACD', 'None'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'SSS: AB = AD, CB = CD, AC shared.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'If \\triangle ABC ≡ \\triangle DEF and AB = 5 cm, what is DE?',
        options: ['5 cm', 'Cannot tell', 'AC + BC', '0'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Corresponding sides equal.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Reflecting a triangle in a line gives a triangle that is …',
        options: ['Congruent (same size, mirror image)', 'Similar but smaller', 'Different shape', 'Larger'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Reflection preserves length and angle.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A regular hexagon can be split into how many congruent equilateral triangles?',
        options: ['6', '4', '8', '12'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Centre + 6 vertices.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A regular hexagon can also be split into how many congruent rhombi?',
        options: ['3', '2', '6', '1'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Three congruent rhombi.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A figure ABCDEF has AB = BC = CD = DE = EF = FA, all equal. Is it equiangular?',
        options: ['Not necessarily — equal sides do not force equal angles for hexagons', 'Yes', 'Only if convex', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Equilateral does not imply equiangular for ≥4-sided polygons.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two triangles, one right-angled and one obtuse, with sides 5, 12, 13 and 5, 12, 13 respectively. Are they congruent?',
        options: ['Yes — both must be right-angled (5-12-13 is a Pythagorean triple)', 'No (they have different shapes)', 'Only similar', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'A 5-12-13 triangle is uniquely a right triangle (SSS).' },
    ],
  },
]

const CH11_PROGRESS_KEY = 'tenali-chapter11-progress'
function ch11_loadProgress() {
  try { return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(CH11_PROGRESS_KEY) || '{}') || {} } catch { return {} }
}
function ch11_saveProgress(p) { try { localStorage.setItem(CH11_PROGRESS_KEY, JSON.stringify(p)) } catch {} }

// --- Custom math renderer for Chapter 11 ----------------------------------
function Ch11Frac({ num, den }) {
  return (
    <span style={{
      display: 'inline-flex', flexDirection: 'column', alignItems: 'center',
      verticalAlign: 'middle', margin: '0 0.18em', lineHeight: 1.05,
      fontSize: '0.95em',
    }}>
      <span style={{ padding: '0 0.4em 0.05em', borderBottom: '1.6px solid currentColor' }}>{num}</span>
      <span style={{ padding: '0.05em 0.4em 0' }}>{den}</span>
    </span>
  )
}
function ch11_subOps(s) {
  return String(s)
    .replace(/\\times/g, '×').replace(/\\div/g, '÷')
    .replace(/\\approx/g, '≈').replace(/\\to\b/g, '→')
    .replace(/\\le\b/g, '≤').replace(/\\ge\b/g, '≥')
    .replace(/\\cdot/g, '·').replace(/\\pm/g, '±')
    .replace(/\\pi/g, 'π').replace(/\\theta/g, 'θ')
    .replace(/\\sqrt\{([^{}]+)\}/g, '√($1)')
    .replace(/\\sqrt(\d+)/g, '√$1')
    .replace(/\\ell\b/g, 'ℓ')
    .replace(/\\circ/g, '°')
    .replace(/\\u2208/g, '∈').replace(/\\u2209/g, '∉')
    .replace(/\\u2205/g, '∅')
    .replace(/\\u222a/g, '∪').replace(/\\u2229/g, '∩')
    .replace(/\\u2286/g, '⊆').replace(/\\u2282/g, '⊂')
    .replace(/\\u2113/g, 'ℓ')
    .replace(/\\u00b0/g, '°')
    .replace(/\\u2019/g, '’')
    .replace(/\\u2032/g, '′')
    .replace(/\\u2013/g, '–')
    .replace(/\\u2660/g, '♠')
    .replace(/\\u2663/g, '♣')
    .replace(/\\u2665/g, '♥')
    .replace(/\\u2666/g, '♦')
    .replace(/\\dot\{(\d)\}/g, '$1̇')
    .replace(/\\\$/g, '$').replace(/\\%/g, '%')
}
function ch11RenderMath(text) {
  if (text == null) return null
  const src = ch11_subOps(text).replace(/\\left\(/g, '(').replace(/\\right\)/g, ')')
  const out = []
  let i = 0, buf = ''
  const flush = () => { if (buf) { out.push(buf); buf = '' } }
  while (i < src.length) {
    if (src.startsWith('\\frac{', i)) {
      flush()
      let j = i + 6, depth = 1
      const ns = j
      while (j < src.length) { if (src[j] === '{') depth++; else if (src[j] === '}') { depth--; if (depth === 0) break } j++ }
      const numStr = src.slice(ns, j); j++
      if (src[j] !== '{') { buf += src.slice(i, j); i = j; continue }
      j++; depth = 1
      const ds = j
      while (j < src.length) { if (src[j] === '{') depth++; else if (src[j] === '}') { depth--; if (depth === 0) break } j++ }
      const denStr = src.slice(ds, j); j++
      out.push(<Ch11Frac key={`f${out.length}`} num={ch11RenderMath(numStr)} den={ch11RenderMath(denStr)} />)
      i = j
    } else if (src[i] === '^') {
      const m = src.slice(i).match(/^\^(-?\d+)/)
      if (m) { flush(); out.push(<sup key={`s${out.length}`} style={{ fontSize: '0.72em', verticalAlign: 'super' }}>{m[1]}</sup>); i += m[0].length }
      else { buf += src[i]; i++ }
    } else { buf += src[i]; i++ }
  }
  flush()
  return out
}

const CH11_AUTO_ADVANCE_MS = 5000

function Chapter11App({ onBack }) {
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState(ch11_loadProgress)
  const [activeId, setActiveId] = useState(null)
  const [phase, setPhase] = useState('teach')
  const [qIdx, setQIdx] = useState(0)
  const [playList, setPlayList] = useState([])
  const [lastWrongSrc, setLastWrongSrc] = useState(null)
  const [selectedIdx, setSelectedIdx] = useState(null)
  const [fillInput, setFillInput] = useState('')
  const [revealed, setRevealed] = useState(false)
  const [isCorrect, setIsCorrect] = useState(false)
  const [autoCountdown, setAutoCountdown] = useState(0)
  const inputRef = useRef(null)
  const autoTimerRef = useRef(null)
  const advanceRef = useRef(() => {})

  const lesson = activeId ? CH11_LESSONS.find(l => l.id === activeId) : null
  const currentSourceIdx = playList[qIdx]
  const currentQ = lesson && currentSourceIdx != null ? lesson.questions[currentSourceIdx] : null
  const isRetry = useMemo(() => {
    if (currentSourceIdx == null) return false
    return playList.slice(0, qIdx).includes(currentSourceIdx)
  }, [playList, qIdx, currentSourceIdx])

  const optionOrder = useMemo(() => {
    if (!currentQ || currentQ.kind !== 'mcq') return []
    return ch11_seededShuffle(currentQ.options.length, `${activeId}-${qIdx}-${currentSourceIdx}-${currentQ.prompt}`)
  }, [activeId, qIdx, currentSourceIdx, currentQ])
  const correctDisplayIdx = useMemo(() => optionOrder.indexOf(currentQ?.correct ?? -1), [optionOrder, currentQ])

  useEffect(() => { ch11_saveProgress(progress) }, [progress])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || revealed) return
    if (currentQ?.kind?.startsWith('fill') && inputRef.current) inputRef.current.focus()
  }, [phase, qIdx, revealed, currentQ])

  const startLesson = (id) => {
    setActiveId(id)
    const lessonRef = CH11_LESSONS.find(l => l.id === id)
    const initial = Array.from({ length: lessonRef.questions.length }, (_, i) => i)
    setPlayList(initial)
    setLastWrongSrc(null)
    const p = progress[id] || {}
    if (p.teachSeen) { setPhase('practice'); setQIdx(p.qIdx || 0) }
    else { setPhase('teach'); setQIdx(0) }
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
  }

  const acknowledgeTeach = () => {
    setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: 0 } }))
    setPhase('practice'); setQIdx(0)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
    setLastWrongSrc(null)
  }

  const submitFill = () => {
    if (!currentQ) return
    if (revealed) { advance(); return }
    const ok = ch11_checkFill(currentQ, fillInput)
    setIsCorrect(ok); setRevealed(true)
    setLastWrongSrc(ok ? null : currentSourceIdx)
  }

  const pickMcq = (displayIdx) => {
    if (!currentQ || revealed || currentQ.kind !== 'mcq') return
    const optSourceIdx = optionOrder[displayIdx]
    const ok = optSourceIdx === currentQ.correct
    setSelectedIdx(displayIdx); setIsCorrect(ok); setRevealed(true)
    setLastWrongSrc(ok ? null : currentSourceIdx)
  }

  const cancelAutoAdvance = () => {
    if (autoTimerRef.current) { clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null }
    setAutoCountdown(0)
  }

  const advance = () => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    if (!lesson) return
    let workingList = playList
    if (lastWrongSrc != null) {
      // Wrong answers go to the END of the lesson — student finishes all
      // fresh questions first, then meets the retry cluster at the tail.
      workingList = [...playList, lastWrongSrc]
      setPlayList(workingList)
      setLastWrongSrc(null)
    }
    const next = qIdx + 1
    if (next >= workingList.length) {
      setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: lesson.questions.length, completed: true } }))
      setPhase('done')
    } else {
      setQIdx(next)
      setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
      setProgress(p => ({ ...p, [activeId]: { ...(p[activeId] || {}), teachSeen: true, qIdx: Math.min(lesson.questions.length, next) } }))
    }
  }
  advanceRef.current = advance

  const jumpToQuestion = (i) => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    if (!lesson) return
    const clamped = Math.max(0, Math.min(playList.length - 1, i))
    setQIdx(clamped); setLastWrongSrc(null)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
    setProgress(p => {
      const cur = p[activeId] || {}
      const saved = Math.max(cur.qIdx || 0, Math.min(lesson.questions.length, clamped))
      return { ...p, [activeId]: { ...cur, teachSeen: true, qIdx: saved } }
    })
  }

  const backToOverview = () => {
    cancelAutoAdvance()
    setActiveId(null); setPhase('teach'); setQIdx(0)
    setSelectedIdx(null); setFillInput(''); setRevealed(false); setIsCorrect(false)
  }

  const resetAll = () => {
    if (!confirm('Reset all Chapter 11 progress?')) return
    setProgress({}); ch11_saveProgress({})
    backToOverview()
  }

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || !revealed) { cancelAutoAdvance(); return }
    const total = Math.round(CH11_AUTO_ADVANCE_MS / 1000)
    setAutoCountdown(total)
    autoTimerRef.current = setInterval(() => {
      setAutoCountdown(prev => {
        if (prev <= 1) {
          clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null
          advanceRef.current()
          return 0
        }
        return prev - 1
      })
    }, 1000)
    return () => { if (autoTimerRef.current) { clearInterval(autoTimerRef.current); autoTimerRef.current = null } }
  }, [phase, revealed, qIdx, activeId])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (phase !== 'practice' || !currentQ) return
    const onKey = (e) => {
      if (revealed) {
        if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') { e.preventDefault(); advance() }
        return
      }
      if (currentQ.kind === 'mcq') {
        const k = e.key
        if (/^[1-9]$/.test(k)) {
          const i = parseInt(k, 10) - 1
          if (i < currentQ.options.length) { e.preventDefault(); pickMcq(i) }
        }
      } else if (currentQ.kind?.startsWith('fill')) {
        if (e.key === 'Enter') { e.preventDefault(); submitFill() }
      }
    }
    window.addEventListener('keydown', onKey)
    return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', onKey)
  }, [phase, qIdx, revealed, currentQ, fillInput, optionOrder])

  // ────────── Overview ──────────
  if (!activeId) {
    const total = CH11_LESSONS.length
    const done = CH11_LESSONS.filter(l => progress[l.id]?.completed).length
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 760, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, alignItems: 'center', marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={onBack}>← Home</button>
          <button className="back-button" style={{ marginLeft: 'auto' }} onClick={resetAll}>Reset progress</button>
        </div>
        <h1 style={{ marginBottom: 4 }}>Chapter 11 — Straight Lines Sequences, Surds & Sets Quadratic Equations</h1>
        <p className="subtitle" style={{ marginTop: 0 }}>
          Cambridge IGCSE Mathematics · {done}/{total} lessons complete
        </p>
        <p style={{ opacity: 0.85, marginTop: 8 }}>
          Pick the next lesson. Each one starts with a short explanation, then a stream of multiple-choice and fill-in-the-blank
          questions — easy warm-ups first, then the actual chapter exercise problems.
        </p>
        <ol style={{ listStyle: 'none', padding: 0, marginTop: 16 }}>
          {CH11_LESSONS.map((l) => {
            const p = progress[l.id] || {}
            const completed = p.completed
            const inProg = !completed && (p.teachSeen || (p.qIdx || 0) > 0)
            return (
              <li key={l.id} style={{ marginBottom: 8 }}>
                <button
                  onClick={() => startLesson(l.id)}
                  style={{
                    width: '100%', textAlign: 'left', padding: '12px 14px',
                    borderRadius: 10,
                    borderLeft: completed ? '4px solid #2ea043' : inProg ? '4px solid #388bfd' : '1px solid var(--clr-border, #444)',
                    borderTop: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    borderRight: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    borderBottom: '1px solid ' + (completed ? '#2ea043' : 'var(--clr-border, #444)'),
                    background: completed
                      ? 'linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(46,160,67,0.32) 0%, rgba(46,160,67,0.18) 100%)'
                      : inProg ? 'rgba(56,139,253,0.10)' : 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
                    color: 'var(--clr-text)',
                    fontWeight: completed ? 600 : 400,
                    cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem',
                    boxShadow: completed ? '0 0 0 1px rgba(46,160,67,0.35) inset' : 'none',
                  }}
                >
                  <span style={{ marginRight: 8 }}>{completed ? '✅' : inProg ? '▶' : '○'}</span>
                  {ch11RenderMath(l.title)}
                  {completed && (
                    <span style={{
                      float: 'right', fontSize: '0.72rem', fontWeight: 700, letterSpacing: '0.5px',
                      color: '#fff', background: '#2ea043', padding: '2px 8px', borderRadius: 10,
                    }}>DONE</span>
                  )}
                  {p.qIdx > 0 && !completed && (
                    <span style={{ float: 'right', fontSize: '0.8rem', opacity: 0.7 }}>{p.qIdx}/{l.questions.length}</span>
                  )}
                </button>
              </li>
            )
          })}
        </ol>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Teach ──────────
  if (phase === 'teach') {
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        </div>
        <h2 style={{ marginBottom: 4 }}>{ch11RenderMath(lesson.title)}</h2>
        <h3 style={{ color: 'var(--clr-accent, #6cf)', marginTop: 16 }}>{ch11RenderMath(lesson.teach.heading)}</h3>
        {lesson.teach.body.map((para, i) => (
          <p key={i} style={{ lineHeight: 1.7, marginBottom: 10, fontSize: '1rem' }}>{ch11RenderMath(para)}</p>
        ))}
        <div style={{
          marginTop: 14, padding: 14, borderRadius: 8,
          background: 'rgba(108,206,255,0.08)', border: '1px solid rgba(108,206,255,0.25)',
          fontSize: '1rem', lineHeight: 1.7,
        }}>
          <strong>Worked example: </strong>{ch11RenderMath(lesson.teach.example)}
        </div>
        {lesson.qFormat && <p style={{ marginTop: 14, fontSize: '0.9rem', opacity: 0.8 }}><em>Note:</em> {lesson.qFormat}</p>}
        <button onClick={acknowledgeTeach} style={{
          marginTop: 18, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8, fontSize: '1rem',
          background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)', color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer',
        }}>I've got it — start questions →</button>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Done ──────────
  if (phase === 'done') {
    const idx = CH11_LESSONS.findIndex(l => l.id === activeId)
    const next = CH11_LESSONS[idx + 1]
    return (
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 16 }}>
          <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        </div>
        <h2>🎉 Lesson complete</h2>
        <p>You finished <strong>{ch11RenderMath(lesson.title)}</strong>.</p>
        {next ? (
          <button onClick={() => startLesson(next.id)} style={{
            marginTop: 12, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8, fontSize: '1rem',
            background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)', color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer',
          }}>Next: {ch11RenderMath(next.title)} →</button>
        ) : (
          <p style={{ marginTop: 16, fontSize: '1.05rem' }}>🎓 You've completed every lesson in Chapter 11.</p>
        )}
        <button onClick={backToOverview} style={{
          marginTop: 12, marginLeft: 8, padding: '10px 18px', borderRadius: 8,
          background: 'transparent', color: 'var(--clr-text)', border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', cursor: 'pointer',
        }}>Back to lessons</button>
      </div>
    )
  }

  // ────────── Practice ──────────
  const sliderMax = Math.max(1, playList.length)
  return (
    <div style={{ maxWidth: 720, margin: '0 auto', padding: '1.5rem 1rem', color: 'var(--clr-text)' }}>
      <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginBottom: 12, alignItems: 'center' }}>
        <button className="back-button" onClick={backToOverview}>← Lessons</button>
        <button className="back-button" onClick={() => setPhase('teach')}>📖 Re-read teach</button>
        <span style={{ marginLeft: 'auto', fontSize: '0.85rem', opacity: 0.75 }}>
          Question {qIdx + 1} / {sliderMax}
          {sliderMax > lesson.questions.length && (
            <span style={{ marginLeft: 6, color: '#f0a020' }}>· {sliderMax - lesson.questions.length} retry queued</span>
          )}
        </span>
      </div>
      <h3 style={{ marginBottom: 8 }}>{ch11RenderMath(lesson.title)}</h3>
      <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 12, marginBottom: 18 }}>
        <span style={{ fontSize: '0.78rem', opacity: 0.65, minWidth: 18, textAlign: 'right' }}>1</span>
        <input
          type="range"
          min={1}
          max={sliderMax}
          value={qIdx + 1}
          onChange={e => jumpToQuestion(parseInt(e.target.value, 10) - 1)}
          aria-label="Jump to question"
          style={{
            flex: 1, accentColor: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
            cursor: 'pointer', height: 22,
          }}
        />
        <span style={{ fontSize: '0.78rem', opacity: 0.65, minWidth: 22 }}>{sliderMax}</span>
      </div>

      <div style={{
        padding: '22px 24px', borderRadius: 10, background: 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
        border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #333)', marginBottom: 16,
        fontSize: '1.25rem', lineHeight: 2.1, textAlign: 'center',
        display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center', minHeight: 80,
        position: 'relative',
      }}>
        {isRetry && (
          <span style={{
            position: 'absolute', top: 8, right: 12, fontSize: '0.7rem', fontWeight: 700,
            letterSpacing: '0.5px', color: '#f0a020', background: 'rgba(240,160,32,0.15)',
            border: '1px solid rgba(240,160,32,0.45)', padding: '2px 8px', borderRadius: 10,
          }}>↻ RETRY</span>
        )}
        <span>{ch11RenderMath(currentQ.prompt)}</span>
      </div>

      {currentQ.kind === 'mcq' ? (
        <div className="options-list">
          {optionOrder.map((srcIdx, displayIdx) => {
            const opt = currentQ.options[srcIdx]
            const isSelected = selectedIdx === displayIdx
            const isCorrectOpt = revealed && correctDisplayIdx === displayIdx
            const isWrongPick = revealed && isSelected && !isCorrect
            return (
              <button
                key={displayIdx}
                className={`option-card ${isSelected ? 'selected' : ''} ${isCorrectOpt ? 'correct-option' : ''} ${isWrongPick ? 'wrong-option' : ''}`}
                onClick={() => pickMcq(displayIdx)}
                disabled={revealed}
                style={{
                  borderColor: isCorrectOpt ? 'var(--clr-correct, #2ea043)' : isWrongPick ? 'var(--clr-wrong, #f85149)' : undefined,
                  background: isCorrectOpt ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.15)' : isWrongPick ? 'rgba(248,81,73,0.15)' : undefined,
                  display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center',
                  position: 'relative', padding: '18px 24px', minHeight: 64,
                  fontSize: '1.1rem', lineHeight: 1.9,
                }}
              >
                <span style={{
                  position: 'absolute', left: 18, top: '50%', transform: 'translateY(-50%)',
                  fontWeight: 700, opacity: 0.6, fontSize: '0.95rem',
                }}>{CH11_OPTION_LABEL[displayIdx]}.</span>
                <span style={{ display: 'inline-flex', alignItems: 'center' }}>{ch11RenderMath(opt)}</span>
              </button>
            )
          })}
        </div>
      ) : (
        <>
          <input
            ref={inputRef}
            type="text"
            value={fillInput}
            onChange={e => setFillInput(e.target.value)}
            disabled={revealed}
            placeholder="Your answer…"
            autoComplete="off"
            style={{
              width: '100%', padding: '14px 16px', fontSize: '1.15rem', borderRadius: 8,
              border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', textAlign: 'center',
              background: revealed ? 'rgba(255,255,255,0.04)' : 'var(--clr-surface, #1c1c1f)',
              color: 'var(--clr-text)', boxSizing: 'border-box',
            }}
          />
          {!revealed && (
            <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 8, marginTop: 12, justifyContent: 'center' }}>
              <button onClick={submitFill} disabled={!fillInput.trim()} style={{
                padding: '10px 22px', borderRadius: 6, background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
                color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem',
                opacity: fillInput.trim() ? 1 : 0.5,
              }}>Check</button>
            </div>
          )}
        </>
      )}

      {revealed && (
        <>
          <div style={{
            marginTop: 16, padding: 16, borderRadius: 8,
            background: isCorrect ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.15)' : 'rgba(248,81,73,0.15)',
            border: `1px solid ${isCorrect ? 'rgba(46,160,67,0.45)' : 'rgba(248,81,73,0.45)'}`,
            fontSize: '1rem', lineHeight: 1.9,
          }}>
            <strong>{isCorrect ? '✅ Correct!' : '❌ Not quite.'}</strong>
            <div style={{ marginTop: 8, display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: 6 }}>
              <strong>Answer:</strong>
              <span>{currentQ.kind === 'mcq'
                ? ch11RenderMath(currentQ.options[currentQ.correct])
                : ch11RenderMath(String(currentQ.answer))}</span>
            </div>
            {currentQ.solution && (
              <div style={{ marginTop: 8, opacity: 0.9, display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: 6 }}>
                <strong>Working:</strong>
                <span>{ch11RenderMath(currentQ.solution)}</span>
              </div>
            )}
          </div>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 12, marginTop: 14, justifyContent: 'center' }}>
            <button onClick={advance} style={{
              padding: '12px 28px', borderRadius: 8, background: 'var(--clr-accent, #2ea043)',
              color: 'white', border: 'none', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '1rem', fontWeight: 600,
            }}>
              {qIdx + 1 === lesson.questions.length ? 'Finish lesson →' : 'Next →'}
            </button>
            <span style={{ fontSize: '0.85rem', opacity: 0.65 }}>
              auto-advance in {autoCountdown}s · or press <kbd style={{ padding: '1px 6px', border: '1px solid var(--clr-border, #555)', borderRadius: 4, fontSize: '0.78rem' }}>Enter</kbd>
            </span>
          </div>
        </>
      )}
    </div>
  )
}

/* =====================================================================
 *  Chapter12App — Cambridge IGCSE Chapter 12 (Straight Lines Sequences, Surds and Sets Quadratic Equations)
 *
 *  Mounted at /chapter9. Same UX as Chapter5App–Chapter8App: ordered
 *  chain of lessons, every one unlocked from the start, slider to jump
 *  questions, MCQ with 1-9 keys + fill-in fallbacks, 5s auto-advance,
 *  completed lessons go green (with readable text), wrong answers
 *  appended to END of playList. See Tenali/skills/igcse-chapter/SKILL.md
 *  for the full pattern.
 * ===================================================================== */

const CH12_OPTION_LABEL = ['1','2','3','4','5','6','7','8','9']

function ch12_seededShuffle(n, key) {
  let h = 2166136261
  for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) { h ^= key.charCodeAt(i); h = Math.imul(h, 16777619) }
  const rand = () => { h = Math.imul(h ^ (h >>> 15), 2246822507); h = Math.imul(h ^ (h >>> 13), 3266489909); return ((h ^= h >>> 16) >>> 0) / 4294967295 }
  const arr = Array.from({ length: n }, (_, i) => i)
  for (let i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) { const j = Math.floor(rand() * (i + 1)); [arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]] }
  return arr
}

function ch12_gcd(a, b) { a = Math.abs(a); b = Math.abs(b); while (b) { [a, b] = [b, a % b] } return a || 1 }
function ch12_reduce(n, d) {
  if (d === 0) return null
  if (d < 0) { n = -n; d = -d }
  const g = ch12_gcd(n, d)
  return { n: n / g, d: d / g }
}
function ch12_parseFrac(raw) {
  if (raw == null) return null
  let s = String(raw).trim().replace(/\\frac\{(-?\d+)\}\{(-?\d+)\}/g, '$1/$2').replace(/\s+/g, ' ').replace(/–/g, '-')
  if (!s) return null
  const mixed = s.match(/^(-?)(\d+)\s+(\d+)\s*\/\s*(\d+)$/)
  if (mixed) {
    const sign = mixed[1] === '-' ? -1 : 1
    const w = +mixed[2], n = +mixed[3], d = +mixed[4]
    if (d === 0) return null
    return ch12_reduce(sign * (w * d + n), d)
  }
  const frac = s.match(/^(-?\d+)\s*\/\s*(-?\d+)$/)
  if (frac) {
    const n = +frac[1], d = +frac[2]
    if (d === 0) return null
    return ch12_reduce(n, d)
  }
  const num = Number(s)
  if (Number.isFinite(num)) {
    if (Number.isInteger(num)) return { n: num, d: 1 }
    const sign = num < 0 ? -1 : 1
    const decimals = (s.split('.')[1] || '').length
    const denom = Math.pow(10, decimals)
    return ch12_reduce(sign * Math.round(Math.abs(num) * denom), denom)
  }
  return null
}
function ch12_fracEqual(a, b) { return a && b && a.n === b.n && a.d === b.d }
function ch12_normalizeNumStr(s) {
  return String(s).trim().replace(/[$,\s%]/g, '').replace(/–/g, '-')
}
function ch12_numEqual(user, expected, tol) {
  const u = parseFloat(ch12_normalizeNumStr(user))
  if (!Number.isFinite(u)) return false
  const t = tol != null ? tol : Math.max(0.005, Math.abs(expected) * 0.005)
  return Math.abs(u - expected) <= t
}

function ch12_checkFill(q, raw) {
  if (!raw || !raw.trim()) return false
  switch (q.kind) {
    case 'fill-num': return ch12_numEqual(raw, q.answer, q.tol)
    case 'fill-frac': {
      const u = ch12_parseFrac(raw)
      const e = ch12_parseFrac(q.answer)
      return ch12_fracEqual(u, e)
    }
    case 'fill-text': return raw.trim().toLowerCase() === String(q.answer).trim().toLowerCase()
    default: return false
  }
}

// --- Lesson catalogue ---------------------------------------------------
// Cambridge IGCSE Chapter 12 — Straight Lines Sequences, Surds and Sets Quadratic Equations
// Sections covered: 12.1 Different types of average (mean, median, mode); 12.2 Comparing using averages and ranges; 12.3 Frequency tables; 12.4 Grouped data (estimating mean, modal class); 12.5 Quartiles and IQR. See uploads PDF p. 378-403.
// nth terms, special sequences, subscript notation); 9.2 Rational and
// irrational numbers (inc. recurring decimals → fractions); 9.3 Surds
// (simplify, +/-, ×/÷, rationalise); 9.4 Sets (notation, ∪/∩/⊂, Venn,
// set builder). See uploads PDF p. 265-311.
const CH12_LESSONS = [
  // ───────────────────── L1: The mode ───────────────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L1',
    title: 'Lesson 1 · The mode',
    teach: {
      heading: 'The most common value',
      body: [
        'The MODE of a data set is the value that appears MOST OFTEN.',
        'A data set can have ONE mode (unimodal), TWO modes (bimodal), or no mode at all (if every value appears equally often).',
        'It is the only "average" that makes sense for non-numerical data — e.g. the modal colour, the modal shoe brand.',
        'For ordered categories, just count occurrences and pick the largest.',
      ],
      example: 'Shoe sizes: 4, 6, 6, 7, 4, 6, 6, 8, 6, 11. The number 6 appears five times — the mode is 6.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mode of 3, 5, 4, 5, 7, 5, 9?',
        options: ['5', '4', '7', '6'], correct: 0,
        solution: '5 appears three times.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mode of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5?',
        options: ['No mode', '5', '3', '1'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Every value appears once.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mode of 4, 4, 7, 7, 8, 9?',
        options: ['Bimodal: 4 and 7', '4', '7', 'No mode'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Both 4 and 7 appear twice — most often.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In a class of 19, shoe sizes: 4 6 7 6 6 7 4 8 6 4 11 6 8 6 5 8 6 8 7. Modal shoe size?',
        options: ['6', '4', '7', '8'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Count: 6 appears most.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mode of {green, blue, blue, red, green, blue}?',
        options: ['blue', 'green', 'red', 'No mode'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Blue appears 3 times; green 2; red 1.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mode is most useful when data is …',
        options: ['categorical', 'continuous and skewed', 'always normal', 'numerical only'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mode handles non-numeric data.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mode of 12, 5, 4, 12, 13, 12?',
        options: ['12', '5', '13', '4'], correct: 0,
        solution: '12 appears 3 times.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A data set has values 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 5, 5, 6. Mode?',
        options: ['4', '5', '3', 'Bimodal: 3 and 4'], correct: 0,
        solution: '4 appears 3 times; others fewer.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Mode of 7, 8, 8, 9, 10, 8, 11.', answer: 8,
        solution: '8 appears most.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In a frequency table, the mode is the value with the …',
        options: ['highest frequency', 'lowest frequency', 'middle frequency', 'first frequency'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Most common = highest frequency.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L2: The median ─────────────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L2',
    title: 'Lesson 2 · The median',
    teach: {
      heading: 'The middle value of an ORDERED list',
      body: [
        'The MEDIAN is the value in the MIDDLE when the data is arranged in order.',
        'Step 1: arrange the data in ASCENDING order.',
        'Step 2: if there are an ODD number of values (n), the median is the value at position \\frac{n+1}{2}.',
        'Step 3: if there are an EVEN number of values, the median is the AVERAGE of the two middle values (positions n/2 and n/2 + 1).',
        'The median is much less affected by extreme values (outliers) than the mean.',
      ],
      example: 'Data 3, 4, 6, 8, 8, 6, 6, 4, 7, 7, 7, 8, 11 (n=13). Sorted: 3 4 4 6 6 6 7 7 7 8 8 8 11. Position (13+1)/2 = 7. Median = 7.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Median of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5?',
        options: ['3', '2', '4', '1'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Middle of 5 ordered values.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Median of 7, 5, 9, 1, 4, 8, 6?',
        options: ['6', '4', '7', '5'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sorted: 1, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9. Middle = 6.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Median of 2, 4, 6, 8?',
        options: ['5', '4', '6', '4.5'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Average of 4 and 6.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Median of 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11?',
        options: ['6', '5', '7', '5.5'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Average of 5 and 7.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Median of 100, 20, 30?',
        options: ['30', '20', '50', '100'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sorted: 20, 30, 100; middle = 30.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'For n = 10 values, median is the average of values in positions …',
        options: ['5 and 6', '4 and 5', '5 only', '5.5 only'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'n/2 = 5 and n/2+1 = 6.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'For n = 21 values, median is the value at position …',
        options: ['11', '10', '11.5', '12'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(n+1)/2 = 11.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Median of 3, 4, 6, 6, 6, 7, 7, 7, 8, 8, 8, 11.', answer: 7,
        solution: '12 values; positions 6 and 7 are both 7; average is 7.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Median of 12, 8, 15, 9, 10, 14.', answer: 11,
        solution: 'Sorted: 8, 9, 10, 12, 14, 15. Middle two: 10 and 12. Mean = 11.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'The median is less affected than the mean by …',
        options: ['extreme outliers', 'small data sets', 'data ordering', 'negative values'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Outliers can pull the mean strongly but barely move the median.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L3: The mean ───────────────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L3',
    title: 'Lesson 3 · The mean',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Mean = \\frac{sum of all values}{number of values}',
      body: [
        'The MEAN (or arithmetic average) of a data set is the total divided by the count.',
        'mean = \\frac{x_1 + x_2 + \\cdots + x_n}{n}.',
        'It uses every value, so it gives a good "central" measure for symmetric data, but is sensitive to outliers.',
        'The mean is often what people just call "the average".',
      ],
      example: 'Data: 4, 6, 8, 6, 6. Mean = (4+6+8+6+6)/5 = 30/5 = 6.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 4, 6, 8, 6, 6?',
        options: ['6', '5', '8', '4'], correct: 0,
        solution: '30/5 = 6.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5?',
        options: ['3', '15', '2.5', '4'], correct: 0,
        solution: '15/5 = 3.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 10, 20, 30?',
        options: ['20', '60', '15', '30'], correct: 0,
        solution: '60/3 = 20.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 7, 7, 8, 8, 9, 9?',
        options: ['8', '7', '9', '7.5'], correct: 0,
        solution: '48/6 = 8.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Sum of 6 values is 48. Mean?',
        options: ['8', '6', '48', '12'], correct: 0,
        solution: '48/6 = 8.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 4 values is 12. Sum?',
        options: ['48', '3', '16', '12'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sum = mean × count = 48.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Mean of 12, 15, 18, 21, 24.', answer: 18,
        solution: '90/5 = 18.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'After 6 tests, your mean was 75. The 7th test you score 89. New mean?',
        options: ['77', '78', '75.5', '82'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Old sum 450 + 89 = 539. New mean 539/7 = 77.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 7 numbers is 12. One value of 8 is removed. New mean of 6?',
        options: ['(\\frac{84-8}{6}) = 12.67', '12', '13', '14'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Old sum 84; new sum 76; 76/6 ≈ 12.67.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Mean of 11.5, 10.5, 12.', answer: 11.33, tol: 0.05,
        solution: '34/3 \\approx 11.33.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L4: Range ──────────────────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L4',
    title: 'Lesson 4 · Range as a measure of spread',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Range = largest \\u2013 smallest',
      body: [
        'The RANGE measures how SPREAD OUT a data set is.',
        'Range = maximum value \\u2013 minimum value.',
        'A SMALL range means the data values are close together (consistent).',
        'A LARGE range means the data is spread out.',
        'Caveat: the range is determined by ONLY the two extreme values, so a single outlier can make it misleadingly large.',
      ],
      example: 'Data: 3, 7, 8, 12, 5. Min = 3, max = 12. Range = 9.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Range of 5, 8, 12, 3, 7?',
        options: ['9', '12', '5', '15'], correct: 0,
        solution: '12 - 3.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Range of -2, 5, 0, 10, 3?',
        options: ['12', '10', '5', '-12'], correct: 0,
        solution: '10 - (-2) = 12.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Range of 7, 7, 7, 7?',
        options: ['0', '7', '28', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Same value \\to no spread.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A small range means the data is …',
        options: ['close together', 'spread out', 'random', 'discrete'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Small range = consistent values.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Range can be misleading when there is …',
        options: ['an outlier', 'a small sample', 'normal data', 'integer data'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'A single extreme value blows up the range.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Two players scoring 5, 5, 5, 5, 30 vs 7, 9, 8, 10, 16. Both means about 10. Range tells us …',
        options: ['Player 1 has bigger range; player 2 is more consistent', 'They are equally consistent', 'Player 2 has bigger range', 'Range is the same'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Player 1 range = 25; player 2 range = 9.' },
      { kind: 'fill-num', prompt: 'Range of 4.5, 7.2, 1.8, 6.0, 5.5.', answer: 5.4, tol: 0.001,
        solution: '7.2 - 1.8.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A class\\u2019s test scores have range 30, mean 65. Another class has range 5, mean 65. Which class is more consistent?',
        options: ['The one with range 5', 'The one with range 30', 'Same', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Smaller range = more consistent.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Set A: 10, 12, 14, 16, 18. Set B: 5, 12, 14, 16, 23. Same mean 14. Which has larger range?',
        options: ['Set B', 'Set A', 'Same', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Set B: 23 - 5 = 18; set A: 18 - 10 = 8.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Range of a single-value data set is …',
        options: ['0', 'Undefined', '1', 'The value itself'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Max = min, so range = 0.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L5: Choosing the right average ─────────────────
  {
    id: 'L5',
    title: 'Lesson 5 · Choosing the right average',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Mode for categories; median for skewed; mean for symmetric',
      body: [
        'Different averages SUMMARISE different things — pick the one that best represents the data.',
        'MODE: best for CATEGORICAL data (favourite colour, modal shoe size). The only average that needs no arithmetic.',
        'MEDIAN: best for skewed data or when there are OUTLIERS — the median resists extreme values.',
        'MEAN: best for SYMMETRIC numerical data with no outliers — uses every value but is pulled by extremes.',
        'Always think about WHICH average tells the story you want to tell.',
      ],
      example: 'House prices in a town often have a few mansions skewing the mean upward; the MEDIAN gives a fairer "typical" value.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Best average for "favourite colour"?',
        options: ['Mode', 'Median', 'Mean', 'Range'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Categorical data \\to mode.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Best average for house prices in a city with a few mansions?',
        options: ['Median', 'Mean', 'Mode', 'Range'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Outliers; median resists.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Best average for symmetric data (e.g. measured heights)?',
        options: ['Mean', 'Mode', 'Median', 'Range'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mean uses every value.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Modal shoe size of a shoe shop\\u2019s sales tells you …',
        options: ['Most-sold size (re-order)', 'Average customer size', 'Smallest size sold', 'Spread of sizes'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mode = most common.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A teacher reports the mean test score is 85% but adds the median is 50%. Likely cause?',
        options: ['One or two very high scores pulled the mean up', 'A typo', 'Equal distribution', 'Most students scored high'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mean > median \\to right-skewed (high outliers).' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In a fair coin-toss simulation of 1000 flips, best summary?',
        options: ['Mean (or proportion)', 'Mode', 'Range', 'Median'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Symmetric numeric \\to mean.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Best average for "favourite ice-cream flavour"?',
        options: ['Mode', 'Median', 'Mean', 'Range'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Categorical.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Survey of household income — typical citizen\\u2019s income is best represented by …',
        options: ['Median', 'Mean', 'Mode', 'Range'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Income data is right-skewed.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'When mean = median = mode, the data is approximately …',
        options: ['Symmetric', 'Skewed left', 'Skewed right', 'Uniform'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'All three coincide for symmetric distributions.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'For continuous data with a long tail to the right, mean is …',
        options: ['greater than median', 'less than median', 'equal to median', 'cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Tail pulls the mean.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L6: Effect of extreme values ───────────────────
  {
    id: 'L6',
    title: 'Lesson 6 · Effect of extreme values',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Outliers move the mean dramatically; barely move the median',
      body: [
        'An OUTLIER is a value much bigger or smaller than the rest of the data.',
        'The MEAN is pulled noticeably by outliers because it uses every value\\u2019s exact size.',
        'The MEDIAN barely moves because it depends only on POSITION in the ordered list.',
        'The MODE may not be affected at all (unless the outlier itself happens to be the most common value).',
        'When deciding whether to remove an outlier, check if it is a measurement error or a genuine extreme value.',
      ],
      example: 'Speeds at a checkpoint: 67.2, 58.3, 128.9, 65.0, 49.0, 55.7. Mean ≈ 70.7 (pulled up by 128.9). Median = (58.3 + 65)/2 = 61.65 — much closer to the typical speed.',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Add an outlier 1000 to the data {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}. What changes more — mean or median?',
        options: ['Mean (much more)', 'Median', 'Both equally', 'Neither'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mean jumps from 3 to about 169; median moves from 3 to 3.5.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Five values 49, 55.7, 58.3, 65, 67.2 — median?',
        options: ['58.3', '65', '67.2', '50'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Middle of 5 sorted values.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Add an extreme value 128.9 to the same set. New mean (to 1 d.p.)?',
        options: ['70.7', '58.3', '67.2', '50.0'], correct: 0,
        solution: '(295.2 + 128.9)/6 = 70.68.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In the same set with 128.9 added, new median?',
        options: ['61.65', '58.3', '65.0', '67.2'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sorted 6 values: average of 58.3 and 65 = 61.65.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Outliers have most influence on …',
        options: ['mean', 'median', 'mode', 'range only'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Mean uses every value\\u2019s size.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'After removing an outlier (data point much higher than the rest), the mean …',
        options: ['decreases', 'increases', 'stays the same', 'depends'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Removing high outlier lowers the mean.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A class\\u2019s mean test score is 75. Remove the lowest score (40). The new mean is …',
        options: ['Higher than 75', 'Lower than 75', 'Equal to 75', 'Cannot tell'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Removing a value below the mean RAISES the mean.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Why do estate agents often quote the MEDIAN house price?',
        options: ['It is less affected by extreme house prices', 'It is easier to compute', 'It is always larger', 'It is the legally required average'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Median resists outliers.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'When you cannot decide whether an extreme value is a measurement error, you should …',
        options: ['Investigate before discarding', 'Always remove it', 'Always keep it', 'Replace with the mean'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Investigate the cause.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Data 5, 6, 7, 8, 100. Median = 7. Mean ≈ 25.2. Which is the better "typical" value?',
        options: ['Median', 'Mean', 'Mode', 'Range'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Median ignores the outlier.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L7: Word problems with averages ────────────────
  {
    id: 'L7',
    title: 'Lesson 7 · Word problems with averages',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Read carefully — which average, which spread?',
      body: [
        'Mixed-data questions often ask for two or three statistics at once.',
        'For "the AVERAGE", check whether the question explicitly says mean / median / mode, or whether you have to choose.',
        'For "the SPREAD" or "the variation", use the range (or later the IQR).',
        'Some questions give the AVERAGE and ask for a missing value: use sum = mean × count.',
        'When comparing several groups, the AVERAGE tells you "typical level" and the RANGE tells you "consistency".',
      ],
      example: 'Gads has scored 48%, 65%, 70%, 60%, 55%, 73%, 60% on six tests so far. Mean = (sum)/6 = 371/6 ≈ 53.0 % — wait, recount. Actually 48+65+70+60+55+73 = 371; mean = 371/6 ≈ 61.83. To raise the mean to 53 % over 7 tests, total must be 7×53 = 371 → 7th score = 371 - 371 = 0 % (clearly an exam error in our worked example — typical real questions give clean numbers).',
    },
    questions: [
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'After 5 tests, Gad\\u2019s mean is 48 %. He needs to take a 6th test and get the mean to be 53 %. What must he score?',
        options: ['78 %', '53 %', '48 %', '60 %'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Total after 6 = 6 × 53 = 318; old total = 240; 6th = 78.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Mean of 4 numbers is 12. A 5th number is added; mean becomes 14. New value?',
        options: ['22', '14', '12', '20'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'New total 5 × 14 = 70; old total 48; new value 22.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Heights of 32 plants average 14.5 cm. After adding one more plant, mean is 14.7 cm. The new plant\\u2019s height?',
        options: ['21.1 cm (≈)', '14.7 cm', '14.5 cm', '0.2 cm'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'New total 33 × 14.7 = 485.1; old 32 × 14.5 = 464; new = 21.1.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: '5 students\\u2019 mean test score is 65. After a teacher review, scores rise by 2 each. New mean?',
        options: ['67', '65', '63', '70'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Adding a constant shifts the mean by the same amount.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A bag of sweets has mass 15 g + change. 50 sweets total mass 770 g. Mean mass per sweet?',
        options: ['15.4 g', '15.0 g', '15.7 g', '20 g'], correct: 0,
        solution: '770/50 = 15.4.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'A factory makes 1.5-kg bags. 60 bags total 92.4 kg. Mean mass?',
        options: ['1.54 kg', '1.50 kg', '1.61 kg', '1.40 kg'], correct: 0,
        solution: '92.4/60 = 1.54.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'In 8 years, a Pacific island recorded heavy storms in years: 4, 5, 6, 5, 7, 8, 4, 3. Mean per year?',
        options: ['5.25', '5', '6', '4.5'], correct: 0,
        solution: '42/8 = 5.25.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same data — modal number of storms?',
        options: ['4 and 5 (bimodal)', '5', '6', '4'], correct: 0,
        solution: '4 and 5 each appear twice.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same data — median?',
        options: ['5', '5.5', '4.5', '6'], correct: 0,
        solution: 'Sorted: 3, 4, 4, 5, 5, 6, 7, 8. Median = (5+5)/2 = 5.' },
      { kind: 'mcq', prompt: 'Same data — range?',
        options: ['5', '4', '8', '3'], correct: 0,
        solution: '8 - 3 = 5.' },
    ],
  },

  // ───────────────────── L8: Comparing data sets ────────────────────────
  {
    id: 'L8',
    title: 'Lesson 8 · Comparing data sets',
    teach: {
      heading: 'Use BOTH average AND spread',
      body: [
        'When comparing two or more data sets, look at BOTH a measure of CENTRE (mean or median) and a measure of SPREAD (range — or later, IQR).',
        'Higher mean \\to higher typical level. Lower range \\to more consistent.',
        'Be careful: identical means do not mean identical data — the spreads can be very different.',
        'Always justify your comparison in WORDS as well as numbers.',
      ],
      example: 'Class A: scores 12, 13, 14, 19, 20. Class B: scores 13, 14, 15, 17, 18. Both have mean = 15.6. But Class A has range 8 and Class B has range 5 — Class B is more consistent.',
